{"title_page": "Hassan al-Qazwini", "text_new": "[[Hujjat al-Islam]] [[Sayyid]] '''Hassan al-Musawi al-Qazwini''' ({{lang-ar|\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0632\u0648\u064a\u0646\u064a}}; born October 16, 1964) is an [[Iraqis|Iraqi]]-[[Americans|American]] [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Imam]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://qazwini.org/biography/|title=Biography|website=Website of Imam Qazwini|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Qazwini|first=Hassan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jlJgdJiL6aAC&dq=hassan+al-qazwini&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHo_uQut7oAhUoTRUIHXIsA8sQ6AEIKDAA|title=American Crescent: A Muslim Cleric on the Power of His Faith, the Struggle Against Prejudice, and the Future of Islam and America|date=2007|publisher=Random House|year=|isbn=978-1-4000-6454-0|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>{{Infobox religious biography|name=Hassan al-Qazwini|death_place=|institute=Islamic Institute of America|period=2015 - Present|resting_place=|students=|denomination=[[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam|Sh\u012b\u02bf\u0101]]|religion=Islam|relatives=[[Moustafa al-Qazwini]] (brother) [[Mahdi al-Modarresi]] (first cousin, once removed) <br/> [[Fadhil al-Milani]] (first cousin & father-in-law )|website=[http://qazwini.org qazwini.org]|children={{hlist|[[Sayed Mohammed Baqer al-Qazwini|Mohammed Baqer]]|Ahmed}}|native_name={{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0632\u0648\u064a\u0646\u064a}}|birth_place=[[Karbala]], [[Iraq]]|nationality=[[Iraqis|Iraqi]] <br/> [[Americans|American]]|death_date=|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1964|10|16|df=y}}|caption=|image=Qazwini.jpg|honorific-prefix=[[Hujjat al-Islam]] [[Sayyid]]|background=#ABE9CC|parents=[[Murtadha al-Qazwini]] (father)|spouse=|title=[[Hujjat al-Islam]]|location=[[Dearborn Heights, Michigan]]|previous_post=[[Imam]] at the [[Islamic Centre of England]], 1997\u20132014}}He was the resident scholar of the [[Islamic Center of America]] for eighteen years. He then founded the Islamic Institute of America in [[Dearborn Heights, Michigan]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nal-Qazwini was born in Karbala in 1964. His father is [[Murtadha al-Qazwini]] from the [[Al-Qazwini (family)|al-Qazwini]] family, and his mother is the daughter of Abd al-Amir Nasrallah, from the [[Al Faiz family#Al Nasrallah|Nasrallah]] family. His family was exiled from Iraq whilst he was still young, and upon settling in Qom, in 1980, he joined the seminary and began his religious education.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pat|first=Mr|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iwaUyarVIMsC|title=Fear God and the Shadow of the Muslim Sword|date=2008|publisher=AuthorHouse|year=|isbn=978-1-4343-9461-3|location=|pages=87|language=en}}</ref> \n\nHe completed his religious education in 1992, and managed to grasp an in-depth understanding of fundamentals of Islamic jurisprudence, and Quranic commentary. During his studies, he administered a prominent Islamic journal called ''an-Nibras'' (The eternal light).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Immigration to the United States ==\n\n==== Los Angeles ====\nal-Qazwini immigrated to the United States in late 1992 along with his family, six years after his father's immigration. He spent four years in [[Los Angeles]], where he directed the Azzahra Islamic Center, which was founded by his father, and conducted several [[Fiqh]] and various other Islamic classes. He realized the importance of disseminating the message of Islam in North America in English, especially to the youth.  While numerous scholars and religious leaders performed a good job reaching out to the Arabic speaking members of the community, the English-speaking generations needed someone who was capable of communicating with them, and so al-Qazwini devoted himself to learning and acquiring a fair grasp of the English language quickly.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Dearborn ====\nIn early 1993, al-Qazwini was invited by the Islamic Center of America (ICA) in [[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]]; the oldest Shia mosque in the United States, as a guest speaker for the Arabic program during [[Ramadan]], where the local community quickly found him responsive to their spiritual and religious needs. The ICA asked him to join them the following year as their guest speaker during Ramadan and then for the first ten nights of [[Muharram]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1997, al-Qazwini established residence in Dearborn, at the behest of the Islamic Center of America. al-Qazwini conducted the [[Friday prayer]] every week, delivering the first sermon in Arabic and the second in English. He also performed an English presentation during the Sunday service, usually aimed at addressing of current issues affecting the local Muslim community as well as the global community at large.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWhilst at the ICA, al-Qazwini established the sub-committee, [[Young Muslim Association]] (YMA) in 1998. The organization was aimed at educating Muslim-American youth, fostering leadership, and creating an environment in which they can actively and effectively channel their efforts in promoting Islam. In it's first five years, the YMA grew to be one of the largest Muslim youth organizations in North America.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6mDiAAAAMAAJ&q=hassan+al-qazwini&dq=hassan+al-qazwini&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHo_uQut7oAhUoTRUIHXIsA8sQ6AEIYzAH|title=The Straight Path|date=2001|publisher=Young Muslim Association of the Islamic Center of America|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Dearborn Heights ====\nIn 2015, al-Qazwini left the ICA and opened his own mosque, known as the Islamic Institute of America. He also established the Muslim Youth Connection (MYC) as the new youth organization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2015/09/22/imam-qazwini-interview-mosque-islamic-institute-islamic-center-of-america-in-dearborn/71306416/|title=Imam Al-Qazwini plans new mosque to educate about Islam|last=Warikoo|first=Niraj|website=Detroit Free Press|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Public appearances ==\nSince the [[September 11 attacks]], al-Qazwini stepped up his efforts to act as an ambassador for [[Islam in the United States|Muslim Americans]], speaking at numerous churches, colleges and universities, hoping to dispel what he sees as common misconceptions about them.\n\nal-Qazwini had been invited to the [[White House]] on several occasions to represent the Shia-Muslim community. \n\nHe has met with Presidents [[Bill Clinton]] and [[George W. Bush]], as well as with then [[United States Senate|senator]] [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcur.org/post/excerpt-imam-hassan-al-qazwini|title=Excerpt from Imam Hassan Al-Qazwini|last=Ziegler|first=Laura|website=www.kcur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0305/11/sun.04.html|title=CNN.com - Transcripts|last=|first=|date=|website=edition.cnn.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040917215258/https://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0305/11/sun.04.html|archive-date=2004-09-17|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\nHe has also received invitations from the U.S. State and Defense Departments. He also made an appearance in the award-winning PBS-broadcast documentary ''[[Muhammad: Legacy of a Prophet]]'' (2002), produced by [http://www.upf.tv/ Unity Productions Foundation].\n\nal-Qazwini met [[Pope Francis]] during the Abrahamic Faiths Initiative in January 14, 2020 in [[Vatican City]]. The initiative brought leaders from Christianity, Judaism and Islam  to work together to promote peaceful expression of faith and the renunciation of violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downriversundaytimes.com/2020/01/17/dearborn-heights-imam-meets-pope-francis/|title=Dearborn Heights Imam meets Pope Francis|website=www.downriversundaytimes.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nal-Qazwini authored two books: \n\n* ''Meditation on Sahihain: A Critique of Sahih Al-Bukhari and Sahih Muslim''\n* ''Prophet Mohammad: The Ethical Prospect''\n\n=== ''American Crescent'' ===\nAl-Qazwini is the author of ''American Crescent: A Muslim Cleric on the Power of His Faith, the Struggle Against Prejudice, and the Future of Islam and America.'' \n\nRashid Khalidi of [[Columbia University]] wrote in ''[[The New York Times]]'': \n<blockquote>\nThis book is many things. It is, first, a personal chronicle of Imam Hassan Qazwini's own trajectory from Karbala, Iraq, where he was born in 1964, to exile in Kuwait and Iran, to Dearborn, Mich., where he currently heads the Islamic Center of America. Second, it is an argument for Qazwini's variety of Shia Islam, rooted in Iraq and Iran and adapted for America. Finally, it is a political statement \u2014 in fact, two of them \u2014 a plea for Muslim Americans to immerse themselves in the life of the United States while simultaneously deepening their identification as Muslims, and also for a particular outcome in Iraq, where Qazwini's father, a leading ayatollah, is Imam of the mosque of Imam Hussein in Karbala.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Khalidi|first=Rashid|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/06/books/review/Khalidi-t.html|title=Red, White, Blue and Green|date=2008-01-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n</blockquote>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nal-Qazwini is married to the daughter of [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad al-Shirazi]]. He has two sons; Muhammad-Baqir and Ahmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alshirazionline.org/news/007.htm|title=Mu'asasat al-Imam al-Shirazi al-Alamiya Bi Washinton Tuhyyi Thikra al- Imam al-Sadiq|last=|first=|date=|website=alshirazionline.org|language=ar|trans-title=Imam al-Shirazi Foundation in Washington revives the memory of Imam Sadiq|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Islam in Detroit]]\n* [[History of the Middle Eastern people in Metro Detroit]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [http://www.qazwini.org/ Official Website]\n*[https://www.iiofa.org/ Islamic Institute of America Website]\n*[http://alqazwini.org/qazwini_org/articles/about_articles/rs_120601.htm Rolling Stone Review]\n* [http://edition.cnn.com/video/?/video/us/2008/04/18/intv.pope.interfaith.mtg.qazwini.cnn CNN Interview]\n* [http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=1084/ 60 Minutes Interview Analysis ]\n* [http://www.itvs.org/9.11/dsl/21.mov ITVS Interview]\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=16352025 NPR Interview]\n* [https://www.npr.org/dmg/dmg.php?prgCode=ATC&showDate=12-May-2005&segNum=4&mediaPref=WM&getUnderwriting=1 NPR Interview 2]\n{{commons category|Hassan Al-Qazwini}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qazwini, Hassan Al-}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:Iraqi emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:People from Karbala]]\n[[Category:Iranian Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslims]]\n", "text_old": "[[Hujjat al-Islam]] [[Sayyid]] '''Hassan al-Musawi al-Qazwini''' ({{lang-ar|\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0632\u0648\u064a\u0646\u064a}}; born October 16, 1964) is an [[Iraqis|Iraqi]]-[[Americans|American]] [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Imam]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://qazwini.org/biography/|title=Biography|website=Website of Imam Qazwini|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Qazwini|first=Hassan|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=jlJgdJiL6aAC&dq=hassan+al-qazwini&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHo_uQut7oAhUoTRUIHXIsA8sQ6AEIKDAA|title=American Crescent: A Muslim Cleric on the Power of His Faith, the Struggle Against Prejudice, and the Future of Islam and America|date=2007|publisher=Random House|year=|isbn=978-1-4000-6454-0|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref>{{Infobox religious biography|name=Hassan al-Qazwini|death_place=|institute=Islamic Institute of America|period=2015 - Present|resting_place=|students=|denomination=[[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam|Sh\u012b\u02bf\u0101]]|religion=Islam|relatives=[[Mahdi al-Modarresi]] (first cousin, once removed)|website=[http://qazwini.org qazwini.org]|children={{hlist|[[Sayed Mohammed Baqer al-Qazwini|Mohammed Baqer]]|Ahmed}}|native_name={{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0632\u0648\u064a\u0646\u064a}}|birth_place=[[Karbala]], [[Iraq]]|nationality=[[Iraqis|Iraqi]] <br/> [[Americans|American]]|death_date=|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1964|10|16|df=y}}|caption=|image=Qazwini.jpg|honorific-prefix=[[Hujjat al-Islam]] [[Sayyid]]|background=#ABE9CC|parents=[[Murtadha al-Qazwini]] (father)|spouse=|title=[[Hujjat al-Islam]]|location=[[Dearborn Heights, Michigan]]|previous_post=[[Imam]] at the [[Islamic Centre of England]], 1997\u20132014}}He was the resident scholar of the [[Islamic Center of America]] for eighteen years. He then founded the Islamic Institute of America in [[Dearborn Heights, Michigan]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nal-Qazwini was born in Karbala in 1964. His father is [[Murtadha al-Qazwini]] from the [[Al-Qazwini (family)|al-Qazwini]] family, and his mother is the daughter of Abd al-Amir Nasrallah, from the [[Al Faiz family#Al Nasrallah|Nasrallah]] family. His family was exiled from Iraq whilst he was still young, and upon settling in Qom, in 1980, he joined the seminary and began his religious education.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pat|first=Mr|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iwaUyarVIMsC|title=Fear God and the Shadow of the Muslim Sword|date=2008|publisher=AuthorHouse|year=|isbn=978-1-4343-9461-3|location=|pages=87|language=en}}</ref> \n\nHe completed his religious education in 1992, and managed to grasp an in-depth understanding of fundamentals of Islamic jurisprudence, and Quranic commentary. During his studies, he administered a prominent Islamic journal called ''an-Nibras'' (The eternal light).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Immigration to the United States ==\n\n==== Los Angeles ====\nal-Qazwini immigrated to the United States in late 1992 along with his family, six years after his father's immigration. He spent four years in [[Los Angeles]], where he directed the Azzahra Islamic Center, which was founded by his father, and conducted several [[Fiqh]] and various other Islamic classes. He realized the importance of disseminating the message of Islam in North America in English, especially to the youth.  While numerous scholars and religious leaders performed a good job reaching out to the Arabic speaking members of the community, the English-speaking generations needed someone who was capable of communicating with them, and so al-Qazwini devoted himself to learning and acquiring a fair grasp of the English language quickly.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==== Dearborn ====\nIn early 1993, al-Qazwini was invited by the Islamic Center of America (ICA) in [[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]]; the oldest Shia mosque in the United States, as a guest speaker for the Arabic program during [[Ramadan]], where the local community quickly found him responsive to their spiritual and religious needs. The ICA asked him to join them the following year as their guest speaker during Ramadan and then for the first ten nights of [[Muharram]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1997, al-Qazwini established residence in Dearborn, at the behest of the Islamic Center of America. al-Qazwini conducted the [[Friday prayer]] every week, delivering the first sermon in Arabic and the second in English. He also performed an English presentation during the Sunday service, usually aimed at addressing of current issues affecting the local Muslim community as well as the global community at large.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nWhilst at the ICA, al-Qazwini established the sub-committee, [[Young Muslim Association]] (YMA) in 1998. The organization was aimed at educating Muslim-American youth, fostering leadership, and creating an environment in which they can actively and effectively channel their efforts in promoting Islam. In it's first five years, the YMA grew to be one of the largest Muslim youth organizations in North America.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6mDiAAAAMAAJ&q=hassan+al-qazwini&dq=hassan+al-qazwini&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHo_uQut7oAhUoTRUIHXIsA8sQ6AEIYzAH|title=The Straight Path|date=2001|publisher=Young Muslim Association of the Islamic Center of America|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== Dearborn Heights ====\nIn 2015, al-Qazwini left the ICA and opened his own mosque, known as the Islamic Institute of America. He also established the Muslim Youth Connection (MYC) as the new youth organization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2015/09/22/imam-qazwini-interview-mosque-islamic-institute-islamic-center-of-america-in-dearborn/71306416/|title=Imam Al-Qazwini plans new mosque to educate about Islam|last=Warikoo|first=Niraj|website=Detroit Free Press|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n== Public appearances ==\nSince the [[September 11 attacks]], al-Qazwini stepped up his efforts to act as an ambassador for [[Islam in the United States|Muslim Americans]], speaking at numerous churches, colleges and universities, hoping to dispel what he sees as common misconceptions about them.\n\nal-Qazwini had been invited to the [[White House]] on several occasions to represent the Shia-Muslim community. \n\nHe has met with Presidents [[Bill Clinton]] and [[George W. Bush]], as well as with then [[United States Senate|senator]] [[Barack Obama]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcur.org/post/excerpt-imam-hassan-al-qazwini|title=Excerpt from Imam Hassan Al-Qazwini|last=Ziegler|first=Laura|website=www.kcur.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0305/11/sun.04.html|title=CNN.com - Transcripts|last=|first=|date=|website=edition.cnn.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040917215258/https://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0305/11/sun.04.html|archive-date=2004-09-17|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> \n\nHe has also received invitations from the U.S. State and Defense Departments. He also made an appearance in the award-winning PBS-broadcast documentary ''[[Muhammad: Legacy of a Prophet]]'' (2002), produced by [http://www.upf.tv/ Unity Productions Foundation].\n\nal-Qazwini met [[Pope Francis]] during the Abrahamic Faiths Initiative in January 14, 2020 in [[Vatican City]]. The initiative brought leaders from Christianity, Judaism and Islam  to work together to promote peaceful expression of faith and the renunciation of violence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downriversundaytimes.com/2020/01/17/dearborn-heights-imam-meets-pope-francis/|title=Dearborn Heights Imam meets Pope Francis|website=www.downriversundaytimes.com|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\nal-Qazwini authored two books: \n\n* ''Meditation on Sahihain: A Critique of Sahih Al-Bukhari and Sahih Muslim''\n* ''Prophet Mohammad: The Ethical Prospect''\n\n=== ''American Crescent'' ===\nAl-Qazwini is the author of ''American Crescent: A Muslim Cleric on the Power of His Faith, the Struggle Against Prejudice, and the Future of Islam and America.'' \n\nRashid Khalidi of [[Columbia University]] wrote in ''[[The New York Times]]'': \n<blockquote>\nThis book is many things. It is, first, a personal chronicle of Imam Hassan Qazwini's own trajectory from Karbala, Iraq, where he was born in 1964, to exile in Kuwait and Iran, to Dearborn, Mich., where he currently heads the Islamic Center of America. Second, it is an argument for Qazwini's variety of Shia Islam, rooted in Iraq and Iran and adapted for America. Finally, it is a political statement \u2014 in fact, two of them \u2014 a plea for Muslim Americans to immerse themselves in the life of the United States while simultaneously deepening their identification as Muslims, and also for a particular outcome in Iraq, where Qazwini's father, a leading ayatollah, is Imam of the mosque of Imam Hussein in Karbala.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Khalidi|first=Rashid|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/06/books/review/Khalidi-t.html|title=Red, White, Blue and Green|date=2008-01-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-10|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n</blockquote>\n\n== Personal Life ==\nal-Qazwini is married to the daughter of [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad al-Shirazi]]. He has two sons; Muhammad-Baqir and Ahmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alshirazionline.org/news/007.htm|title=Mu'asasat al-Imam al-Shirazi al-Alamiya Bi Washinton Tuhyyi Thikra al- Imam al-Sadiq|last=|first=|date=|website=alshirazionline.org|language=ar|trans-title=Imam al-Shirazi Foundation in Washington revives the memory of Imam Sadiq|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Islam in Detroit]]\n* [[History of the Middle Eastern people in Metro Detroit]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [http://www.qazwini.org/ Official Website]\n*[https://www.iiofa.org/ Islamic Institute of America Website]\n*[http://alqazwini.org/qazwini_org/articles/about_articles/rs_120601.htm Rolling Stone Review]\n* [http://edition.cnn.com/video/?/video/us/2008/04/18/intv.pope.interfaith.mtg.qazwini.cnn CNN Interview]\n* [http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=1084/ 60 Minutes Interview Analysis ]\n* [http://www.itvs.org/9.11/dsl/21.mov ITVS Interview]\n* [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=16352025 NPR Interview]\n* [https://www.npr.org/dmg/dmg.php?prgCode=ATC&showDate=12-May-2005&segNum=4&mediaPref=WM&getUnderwriting=1 NPR Interview 2]\n{{commons category|Hassan Al-Qazwini}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qazwini, Hassan 