{"title_page": "Whiteness studies", "text_new": "{{Over-coverage|region=the United States|date=November 2019}} {{More footnotes|date=December 2017}}\n\n'''Whiteness studies''' is the study of the structures that produce [[white privilege]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/14/books/noel-ignatiev-dead.html |title=Noel Ignatiev, 78, Persistent Voice Against White Privilege, Dies|authorlink=Neil Genzlinger|author=Neil Genzlinger|quote=\u201cHow the Irish Became White\u201d is among a group of books that have been foundational to what became known as whiteness studies, a field that examines the structures that produce white privilege.|date=November 14, 2019|work=[[New York Times]]}}</ref> the examination of what whiteness is when analyzed as a race, a culture, and a source of [[systemic racism]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2015/7/24/9023721/white-whiteness-race-identity |title=White people have a race \u2014 but everyone flips out when we talk about it|authorlink=|author=Jen\u00e9e Desmond-Harris|quote=Examining what whiteness is \u2014 analyzing it as a race, a culture, and a concept that has fueled racism \u2014 isn't new, particularly in academia.|date=July 24, 2015|publisher=[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> and the exploration of other [[social phenomena]] generated by the societal compositions, perceptions and group behaviours of [[white people]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/03/30/prof-receives-hate-mail-over-problem-of-whiteness/70697394/ |title=Professor gets hate mail over 'Problem of Whiteness' |authorlink=|author=Kaila White|quote=Academics and researchers have taught classes and published works on \"Whiteness\" and the field of \"critical Whiteness studies\" since the '90s. \"Whiteness\" is an academic term that refers not to race but to a multilayered concept: how whites are viewed by society, how they view themselves, and the implications of those perceptions, such as social norms and discrimination.|date=March 31, 2015|publisher=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> An [[interdisciplinary]] arena of inquiry that has developed beginning in the [[United States]] from [[white trash]] studies and [[Critical race theory|critical race studies]], particularly since the late 20th century.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kennedy|first=Tammie M.|last2=Middleton|first2=Joyce Irene|last3=Ratcliffe|first3=Krista|last4=Welch|first4=Kathleen Ethel|last5=Prendergast|first5=Catherine|last6=Shor|first6=Ira|last7=West|first7=Thomas R.|last8=Cushman|first8=Ellen|last9=Kendrick|first9=Michelle|last10=Albrecht|first10=Lisa|date=2005-10-01|title=Symposium: Whiteness Studies|journal=Rhetoric Review|volume=24|issue=4|pages=359\u2013402|doi=10.1207/s15327981rr2404_1|issn=0735-0198}}</ref> It is focused on what proponents{{Who|date=November 2019}} describe as the cultural, historical and sociological aspects of people identified as white, and the [[social construction]] of \"whiteness\" as an ideology tied to social status.\n\nPioneers in the field include [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] (\"Jefferson Davis as a Representative of Civilization\", 1890; ''[[Darkwater]]'', 1920), [[James Baldwin]] (''[[The Fire Next Time]]'', 1963), [[Theodore W. Allen]] (''The Invention of the White Race,'' 1976, expanded in 1995), [[Ruth Frankenberg]] (''White Women, Race Matters: The Social Construction of Whiteness'', 1993), author and literary critic [[Toni Morrison]] (''[[Playing in the Dark: Whiteness and the Literary Imagination]]'', 1992) and historian [[David Roediger]] (''The Wages of Whiteness'', 1991).\n\nBy the mid-1990s, numerous works across many disciplines analyzed whiteness, and it has since become a topic for academic courses, research and anthologies. Some syllabuses associate the dismantling of [[white supremacy]] as a stated aim in the understanding of whiteness,<ref name=\"washingtonpost2015\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/11/12/a-course-originally-called-the-problem-of-whiteness-returns-to-asu-as-racial-tensions-boil-over-on-campuses/ |title=A course originally called 'The Problem of Whiteness' returns to Arizona State|authorlink=|author=Yanan Wang|quote=The syllabus described Critical Whiteness Studies as a field \u201cconcerned with dismantling white supremacy in part by understanding how whiteness is socially constructed and experienced.\u201d|date=November 12, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> while other sources view the field of study as primarily educational and exploratory, such as in questioning the objectivity of generations of works produced in intellectual spheres dominated by white scholars.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cjr.org/special_report/the-man-who-saw-himself.php |title=The Man Who Saw Himself|authorlink=|author=Matthew Shaer|quote=The field of \u201cWhiteness Studies,\u201d as it is often termed in academic circles, has existed for decades. Writers ... have looked at the way whiteness has evolved as an ideology and a construct. In doing so, they have called into question the supposed objectivity of the work of generations of straight, white, male scholars|date=December 1, 2015|work=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]}}</ref>\n\nA central tenet of whiteness studies is a reading of history and its effects on the present that is inspired by [[postmodernism]] and [[historicism]], in which the very concept of [[Racism|racial superiority]] is said to have been socially constructed in order to justify discrimination against non-whites. Since the 19th century, some writers have argued that the [[Phenotype|phenotypical]] significances attributed to specific races are without biological association, and that race is therefore not a valid biological concept.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://academic.udayton.edu/race/01race/race.htm|title=What is Race?|last=Randall|first=Vernellia R.|website=academic.udayton.edu|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Many scientists have demonstrated that racial theories are based upon an arbitrary clustering of phenotypical categories and [[customs]], and can overlook the problem of gradations between categories.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Obasogie|first1=Osagie|title=Return of the race myth?|journal=New Scientist|date= July 1, 2009|volume=203|issue=2715|pages=22\u201323|accessdate=|bibcode=2009NewSc.203...22O|doi=10.1016/S0262-4079(09)61767-X}}</ref> Thomas K. Nakayama and Robert L. Krizek write about whiteness as a \"strategic rhetoric,\" asserting, in the essay \"Whiteness: A Strategic Rhetoric\", that whiteness is a product of \"discursive formation\" and a \"rhetorical construction\". Nakayama and Krizek write, \"there is no 'true essence' to 'whiteness': there are only historically contingent constructions of that social location.\"<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Nakayama | first1 = Thomas K. | last2 = Krizek | first2 = Ro L.bert | title = Readings in Rhetorical Criticism | chapter = Whiteness: A Strategic Rhetoric | edition = 3 |editor = Carl Burgchardt | isbn = 978-1-891136-12-2| date = January 1, 2005 }}</ref> Nakayama and Krizek also suggest that by naming whiteness, one calls out its centrality and reveals its invisible, central position. Whiteness is considered normal and neutral, therefore, to name whiteness means that one identifies whiteness as a rhetorical construction that can be dissected to unearth its values and beliefs.\n\nMajor areas of research in whiteness studies include the nature of [[white privilege]] and white identity, the historical process by which a white [[Race (human categorization)|racial identity]] was created, the relation of culture to white identity, and possible processes of social change as they affect white identity.\n\n== Definitions of whiteness ==\nZeus Leonardo defines whiteness as \"a racial discourse, whereas the category \u2018white people\u2019 represents a socially constructed identity, usually based on\u00a0skin color\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leonardo|first=Zeus|date=March 2002|title=The Souls of White Folk: Critical pedagogy, whiteness studies, and globalization discourse|journal=Race Ethnicity and Education|volume=5|issue=1|pages=29\u201350|doi=10.1080/13613320120117180|issn=1361-3324}}</ref> Steve Garner notes that \"whiteness has no stable consensual meaning\" and that \"the meanings attached to 'race' are always time- and place-specific, part of each national racial regime\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Whiteness : an introduction|last=Garner, Steve, 1963-|date=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-40363-4|location=London|oclc=80358978}}</ref>\n\n==Development of the field==\nStudies of whiteness as a unique identity could be said to begin among [[black people]], who needed to understand whiteness to survive, particularly in slave societies such as the American colonies and United States.<ref name=hooksRepresentations>[[bell hooks]], \"Representations of Whiteness in the Black Imagination\", ''Black Looks'' (1992); republished in Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998).</ref><ref name=Ganley>{{cite journal | last = Ganley | first = Toby | title = What's all this talk about whiteness? | journal = Dialogue | volume = 1 | issue = 2 | pages = 12&ndash;30 | publisher = [[University of Queensland]] | date = 2003 | url = http://www.polsis.uq.edu.au//dialogue/vol-1-2-4.pdf | ref = harv | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130428181555/http://www.polsis.uq.edu.au//dialogue/vol-1-2-4.pdf | archive-date = 2013-04-28 }} ([https://dialoguejournal.org.au/archives/ Link to journal.])</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Roediger | first = David | title = Critical studies of whiteness, USA: origins and arguments | journal = [[Theoria (sociology journal)|Theoria]] | volume = 48 | issue = 98 | pages = 72&ndash;98 | publisher = [[Berghahn Books|Berghahn]] | doi = 10.3167/004058101782485511 | date = 1 December 2001 | ref = harv }}</ref> An important theme in this literature is, beyond the general \"invisibility\" of blacks to whites, the unwillingness of white people to consider that black people study them anthropologically.<ref name=hooksRepresentations/> American author [[James Weldon Johnson]] wrote in his 1912 novel ''[[The Autobiography of an Ex-Colored Man]]'' that \"colored people of this country know and understand the white people better than the white people know and understand them\".<ref>[[James Weldon Johnson]], ''[http://etc.usf.edu/lit2go/64/the-autobiography-of-an-ex-colored-man/ The Autobiography of an Ex-Colored Man]'', Boston: Sherman, French, and Co., 2012; Chapter 2.</ref><ref>Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998), p. 5.</ref> Author [[James Baldwin]] wrote and spoke extensively about whiteness, defining it as a central social problem and insisting that it was choice, not a biological identity.<ref>Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998), pp. 20\u201321. \"No thinker so fully brought together the many dimensions of African-American studies of whiteness as James Baldwin. [...] Adopting and treasuring a white identity is, he wrote, 'absolutely a moral choice' since 'there are no white people.'\"</ref><ref>James Baldwin, \"On being 'white' and other lies\", ''Essence'', 1984; republished in Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998).</ref> In ''[[The Fire Next Time]]'' (1963), a non-fiction book on race relations in the United States, Baldwin suggests that \n<blockquote>\"White people in this country will have quite enough to do in learning how to accept and love themselves and each other, and when they have achieved this\u2014which will not be tomorrow and may very well be never\u2014the Negro problem will no longer exist, for it will no longer be needed.\"<ref>[[James Baldwin]], ''The Fire Next Time'', New York: Dial Press, 1963; republished in New York by Vintage International, 1993; p. 22.</ref></blockquote>A major black theory of whiteness connects this identity group with acts of [[terrorism]]\u2014i.e., slavery, rape, torture, and lynching\u2014against black people, who were treated as sub-human.<ref>Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998), pp. 15\u201316. \"Equally compelling African\u2013American studies treat whiteness as a species of terror. [...] [[Paul Gilroy]]'s recent ''The Black Atlantic'' uncompromisingly calls upon the tradition of connecting the terrors of the trade in black bodies, the bloodiness of slave control, and the soul-killing violence of racial exploitation with the total experience of whiteness by people of colors. [[bell hooks]] makes much the same points regarding the circumstances under which African Americans encounter and represent whiteness. Other black thinkers have carried this insight still further. They contend that whiteness is also experienced through terror by whites, who find and reproduce unity by committing and more often by witnessing acts of violence. Slave tales and autobiographies, for example, at times insisted upon the centrality of stealing humans, breaking up families, 'patrolling' plantations, and committing rape to the growth of a white identity.\"</ref>\n\nWhite academics in the United States and the United Kingdom (UK) began to study whiteness as early as 1983, creating the idea of a discipline called \"whiteness studies\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Murray | first = Albert | title = Omni-Americans: Some Alternatives to the Folklore of White Supremacy | publisher = Vintage | year = 1983 | oclc = 1020212158}}</ref> The \"[[canon wars]]\" of the late 1980s and 1990s, a political controversy over the centrality of white authors and perspectives in United States culture, led the scholar [[Shelley Fisher Fishkin]] to ask \"how the imaginative construction of 'whiteness' had shaped American literature and American history\".<ref name=\"Fishkin_interrogate\">{{cite journal | last = Fishkin | first = Shelley Fisher | author-link = Shelley Fisher Fishkin | title = Interrogating \"Whiteness,\" Complicating \"Blackness\": Remapping American Culture | journal = [[American Quarterly]] | volume = 47 | issue = 3 | pages = 428&ndash;466 | publisher = [[Johns Hopkins University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/2713296 | date = September 1995 | quote = In this essay I will provide a brief overview of over a hundred books and articles from fields including literary criticism, history, cultural studies, anthropology, popular culture, communication studies, music history, art history, dance history, humor studies, philosophy, linguistics, and folklore, all published between 1990 and 1995 or forthcoming shortly. Taken together, I believe, they mark the early 1990s as a defining moment in the study of American culture. | ref = harv | jstor = 2713296 | hdl = 2152/31168 }}</ref>{{rp|430}} The field developed a large body of work during the early 1990s, Fishkin describes it extending across the disciplines of \"literary criticism, history, cultural studies, sociology, anthropology, popular culture, communication studies, music history, art history, dance history, humor studies, philosophy, linguistics, and folklore\".<ref name=\"Fishkin_interrogate\" />\n\nAs of 2004, according to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', at least 30 institutions in the United States including [[Princeton University]], the [[University of California at Los Angeles]], the [[University of New Mexico]] and [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] offer, or have offered, courses in whiteness studies. Teaching and research around whiteness often overlap with research on [[post-colonial theory]] and [[orientalism]] taking place in the Arts and Humanities, Sociology, Literature, Communications, and Cultural and Media Studies faculties and departments, among others (e.g. Kent, Leeds). Also heavily engaged in whiteness studies are practitioners of [[anti-racism|anti-racist education]], such as [[Betita Martinez]] and the Challenging White Supremacy workshop.\n\nOne contribution to White Studies is [[Rich Benjamin]]'s ''[[Searching for Whitopia|Searching for Whitopia: An Improbable Journey to the Heart of White America]]''. The book examines white social beliefs and white anxiety in the contemporary United States\u2014in the context of enormous demographic, cultural, and social change.  The book is often taught as a primer in White Studies on white racial identity in a \"post-racial\" US.<ref>{{cite book | last = Benjamin | first = Rich | title = Searching for Whitopia: An Improbable Journey to the Heart of White America | publisher = Hyperion | location = New York | year = 2009 | isbn = 9781401322687 }}</ref>\n\nAnother major contribution to whiteness studies is the analysis of whiteness as a phenomenon, not just localized to the US and Western Hemisphere, but also in the context of other post-colonial metropoles such as the Netherlands.  [[Gloria Wekker]]\u2019s ''White Innocence: Paradoxes of Colonialism and Race'' excavates the immutability and fluidity of white identity and its relationship to innocence in the context of post-colonial [[Netherlands]] in the first decade of the twenty-first century. Wekker identifies white innocence as a contemporary construction and denial [aggressive national forgetting] of the Netherlands role and proximity to European imperialism, racial stratification and hierarchy, and its contributions to the making of contemporary constructions of national belonging and cultural normativity (autochtoon vs. allochtonen).\n\nIn Wekker\u2019s analysis, although a majority of the residents of the Netherlands are migrants, the process of stratifying Dutch from \u201cOther\u201d is facilitated through skin tone and non-Christian religious practices (\u201cdeviant\u201d, non-White religions). In Wekker's account, the process of racialization is reserved for mid-to-late twentieth century migrant groups [i.e. Muslims, Black Surinamese, Black Antilleans], interchangeably as a means of delineating groups outside the constructed immutable \u201cnorms\u201d of Dutch society. Ultimately, Wekker is illuminating the cultural and rhetorical maneuvering that occurs within Dutch popular culture, educational spaces, and national discourses that facilitate a normalizing, non-identity to whiteness and how this very concept is intricately connected to a longer historical nineteenth-century racial grammar that accompanied imperial expansion.<ref>{{cite book | last = Wekker | first = Gloria | title = White Innocence: Paradoxes of Colonialism and Race | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham | year = 2016 | isbn = 9780822360759 }}</ref>\n\n==Areas of study==\n===Whiteness===\nWhiteness studies draws on research into the definition of race, originating with the United States but applying to racial stratification worldwide. This research emphasizes the historically recent [[social construction]] of white identity. As stated by [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] in 1920: \"The discovery of a personal whiteness among the world's peoples is a very modern thing,\u2014a nineteenth and twentieth century matter, indeed.\"<ref>W. E. B. Du Bois, ''Darkwater'' (1920); republished in Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998), p. 184.</ref> The discipline examines how white, Native, and African/black identities emerged in interaction with the institutions of slavery, colonial settlement, citizenship, and industrial labor. Scholars such as [[Winthrop Jordan]]<ref>{{cite book | last = Jordan | first = Winthrop D. | author-link = Winthrop Jordan | title = White over Black: American Attitudes Toward the Negro, 1550-1812 | publisher = Omohundro Institute of Early Armerian History and Culture, Wiliamsburg, Virginia | location = Chapel Hill | year = 2012 | edition = 2nd | isbn = 9781469600765 }}</ref> have traced the evolution of the legally defined line between \"blacks\" and \"whites\" to colonial government efforts to prevent cross-racial revolts among unpaid laborers.\n\nPrinceton professor [[Nell Irvin Painter]], in her 2010 book ''[[The History of White People]],''<ref>{{cite book | last = Painter | first = Nell Irvin | title = The History of White People | publisher = [[W. W. Norton & Company]] | location = New York and London | year = 2010 | isbn = 9780393049343 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/historyofwhitepe00pain }}</ref> says the idea of whiteness is not just a matter of biology but also includes \"concepts of labor, gender, class, and images of personal beauty\".(p. xi) The earliest European societies, including the Greeks and Romans, had no concept of race and classified people by ethnicity and social class, with the lowest class being slaves, most of whom were European in origin.(p. xi) Race science, developed in Europe in the 1800s, included intense analysis of different groups of Europeans, who were classified as belonging to three or four different races, with the most admirable being from northern Europe.(pp.&nbsp;215&ndash;6) From the early days of the United States, whiteness was a criterion for full citizenship and acceptance into society. The American definition of whiteness evolved over time; initially groups such as Jews and southern Europeans were not regarded as white, but as skin color became the primary criterion, they were gradually accepted. Painter argues that in the 21st century the definition of whiteness - or more precisely the definition of \"nonblackness\" - has continued to expand, so that now \"The dark of skin who happen to be rich ... and the light of skin from any (racial background) who are beautiful, are now well on their way to inclusion.\"(pp.&nbsp;389&ndash;90.)\n\nAcademic Joseph Pugliese is among writers who have applied whiteness studies to an [[Australia]]n context, discussing the ways that [[Indigenous Australians]] were marginalized in the wake of British colonization of Australia, as whiteness came to be defined as central to Australian identity, diminishing [[Aboriginal identity]] in the process.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Perera | first1 = Suvendrini | last2 = Pugliese | first2 = Joseph | title = White Law of the Biopolitical | journal = Journal of the European Association of Studies on Australia | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages = 87&ndash;100 | publisher = European Association of Studies on Australia | date = 2012 | url = http://www.easa-australianstudies.net/node/295 | ref = harv }} [http://www.easa-australianstudies.net/files/jeasa4spererajpugliese16.pdf Pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Perera | first1 = Suvendrini | last2 = Pugliese | first2 = Joseph | title = Death in a dry river: black life, white property, parched justice | journal = Somatechnics | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages = 65&ndash;86 | publisher = [[Edinburgh University Press]] | doi = 10.3366/soma.2011.0007 | date = 2011 | ref = harv }}</ref> Pugliese discusses the 20th-century [[White Australia policy]] as a conscious attempt to preserve the \"purity\" of whiteness in Australian society.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Pugliese | first = Joseph | title = Race as Category Crisis: Whiteness and the Topical Assignation of Race | journal = Social Semiotics | volume = 12 | issue = 2 | pages = 149&ndash;168 | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/103503302760212078 | date = 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Willard | first = Myra | title = History of the White Australia policy to 1920  |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofwhiteau0000will | url-access = registration | publisher = Frank Cass and Company | location = Carlton, Victoria  |origyear=1923 | year = 1967 | isbn = 9780714610368 }}</ref> Likewise Stefanie Affeldt considers whiteness \"a concept not yet fully developed at the time the first convicts and settlers arrived down under\" <ref>Affeldt, Stefanie. ''Consuming Whiteness'', p. 14.</ref> which, as a social relation, had to be negotiated and was driven forward in particular by the labour movement. Eventually, with the Federation of Australia, \"[o]verlaying social differences, the shared membership in the 'white race' was the catalyst for the consolidation of the Australian colonies as the Commonwealth of Australia\".<ref>Affeldt, Stefanie. ''Consuming Whiteness'', p. 15.</ref>\n\n===White backlash===\n{{main|White backlash}}\nWhite backlash or white rage in association with or as a consequence of whiteness is an area of investigation in whiteness studies. Sociologist [[Matthew Hughey]] has described this examination of racially-based backlash within its historical context; \"Another approach to the study of whiteness centres on the white \"back-lash\" against the advances born from the [[civil rights movement]].\"<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Matthew Hughey|author=Matthew Hughey|title=White Bound: Nationalists, Antiracists, and the Shared Meanings of Race|date=2012|publisher=[[Stanford University Press]]|pages=10|isbn=978-0804776950|chapter=Racists vs Antiracists?|quote=}}</ref>\n\nPolitical scientist [[Danielle Allen]] has analyzed the intersection of whiteness with North American demographic changes, stating how they can \"provoke resistance from those whose well-being, status and self-esteem are connected to historical privileges of 'whiteness'\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/donald-trumps-troubling-us-constituency-2015-9 |title=Trump is tapping into a troubling US constituency |authorlink=Danielle Allen|author=Danielle Allen|quote=|date=September 7, 2015 |work=[[Business Insider]]}}</ref> Discussing the method of this resistance, [[Veronica Strong-Boag]]'s co-edited ''Rethinking Canada: The Promise of Women's History'' explores how white backlash in Canada attempts to frames the defending of white interests as a \"defence of national identity\", rather than an acknowledgement of the political action of whiteness.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=|author=Mary-Jo Nadeau|editor1=Veronica Jane Strong-Boag|editor2=Mona Lee Gleason|editor3=Adele Perry|title=Rethinking Canada: The Promise of Women's History|date=2006|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|pages=389|isbn=978-0195431728|chapter=Who is Canadian Now?: Feminism and the Politics of Nation After. September 11|quote=A sense of insecurity, uncertainty and crisis fed a backlash to the gains made by minorities, a backlash which was not framed as an overt defence of whiteness, but rather, like the books described above, as a defence of national identity}}</ref>\n\nScholar [[George Yancy]] has explored the societal response to perceived loss of racial privilege in his 2018 book ''Backlash''; how reactions derived from whiteness fluctuate between [[Robin DiAngelo]]'s concept of [[white fragility]] versus the more extreme backlashes throughout history.<ref>{{cite book|title=Backlash: What Happens When We Talk Honestly about Racism in America|author1=George Yancy|authorlink1=George Yancy|quote=The responses that I received, however, speak to something more extreme than just reactionary or unreceptive responses. Rather than \"white fragility\", these responses are ones that speak to deep forms of white world-making|date=2018|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|location=|isbn=978-1538104057|page=50|edition=}}</ref>\n\n===White education===\nThe study of white education and its intersection with whiteness is a continuing area of research in whiteness studies. Scholarly investigation has critiqued white-derived education as inevitably for the benefit of, organized by, and oriented towards white people.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Maryemma Graham|editor2=Sharon Pineault-Burke|editor3=Marianna White Davis|authorlink=|author=Ann Louise Keating|title=Teaching African American Literature|chapter=\"Interrogating \"Whiteness,\" (De)Constructing \"Race\"|date=1998|publisher=[[Routledge]]|pages=195|isbn=978-0415916967|quote=At this early stage in own interrogation of \"whiteness\" I was tempted to draw on my African ancestry, disavow my \"white\" education, and entirely separate myself (intellectually, if not physically) from the so-called \"white race\". Interrogations of \"whiteness\" have had similar but far more extreme impact on my students.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jan/23/the-toxicity-of-low-expectations-limits-indigenous-students|title=The toxicity of low expectations limits Indigenous students |edition=IndigenousX|authorlink=|author=Michelle Kerrin|quote=If you have been the token Indigenous student in your class, or if you have simply entered white education spaces, you may understand the complexities of having to negotiate your Indigenous identity in order to achieve the narrative of success.|date=January 23, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> [[Horace Mann Bond]] was one of the early scholars to identify bias and privilege operating in white education systems. Using his role as Secretary of the [[Massachusetts State Board of Education]] to promote universal public education in the US, Bond critiqued suggestions [[African Americans]] were not intelligent enough to participate in the same schools as [[white Americans]] and campaigned against calls for literacy tests for suffrage. He challenged the [[Southern Manifesto]] and identified bias for funding white education, rather than universal funding, even within the reformist movement for desegregated schools.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=|author=Shelley Sallee|title=The Whiteness of Child Labor Reform in the New South|date=2004|publisher=[[University of Georgia Press]]|pages=106\u2013107|isbn=978-0820325705|chapter=Whiteness of Reform|quote=One reason references to literacy qualifications for suffrage remained an issue that shaped racialized rhetoric of reform was because competition for education funds was tight and reformers could use the idea that African Americans might surpass whites to bolster their case for creating funding for white education.}}</ref>\n\nWhiteness and privilege have continued in US education after [[Jim Crow laws|Jim Crow]] versions of the [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregationist]] ideology have lost their legitimacy due to legal and political failures.<ref>{{cite book | last = Irons | first = Jenny | chapter = Conclusion: Legitimacy, Whiteness, and Racism | chapter-url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0I5mA3Ui6ZQC&pg=PT199 | title = Reconstituting Whiteness: the Mississippi State Sovereignty Commission | pages = 198\u2013199 | publisher = Vanderbilt University Press | location = Nashville, Tennessee | year = 2010 | isbn = 9780826516855 }}</ref> Privacy and individualism discourses mask white fear and newer forms of exclusion in contemporary education according to scholar, Charles R. Lawrence III.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Lawrence | first = Charles R., III. | title = Forbidden Conversations: On Race, Privacy, and Community (A Continuing Conversation with John Ely on Racism and Democracy) | journal = Yale Law Journal | volume = 114 | issue = 6 | pages = 1359\u20131377 | jstor = 4135742 | date = 2005 | url = https://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/ylj/vol114/iss6/5 | ref = harv }} [https://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=4953&context=ylj Pdf.]</ref>\n\n===White identity===\n{{main|White identity}}\nAnalyzing whiteness to forge new understandings of white identity has been a field of exploration for academics since the publications which largely founded modern whiteness studies in the mid-1990s. In exploring [[Ruth Frankenberg]]'s works, and her interchanging use of the two concepts, the separation has been examined by scholars attempting to intellectually \"disengtangle each from the other\".<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ravi Malhotra|author2=Morgan Rowe|editor1=Leda M. Cooks|editor2=Jennifer S. Simpson|authorlink1=|authorlink2=|title=Whiteness, Pedagogy, Performance: Dis/Placing Race|chapter=Rowe and Malhotra|date=2007|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|location=|isbn=978-0739114629|quote=Whiteness studies effectively demonstrate the connection between white identities and whiteness as a social construction, they do not reveal how we can disentangle each from the other ... The slippage between white identity and whiteness that occurs in Frankenberg's text is widespread, particularly within the foundational texts within the field of whiteness studies.}}</ref>\n\nSociologist [[Howard Winant]], favoring a deconstructionist (rather than abolitionist) study of whiteness, suggests this methodology can help redefine and reorient understanding of white identity.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Birgit Brander Rasmussen|editor2=Irene J. Nexica|editor3=Eric Klinenberg|editor4=Matt Wray|authorlink=Howard Winant|author=Howard Winant|title=The Making and Unmaking of Whiteness|chapter=Howard Winant|date=2001|publisher=[[Duke University Press]]|pages=107|isbn=978-0822327400|quote=I understand deconstructing whiteness to mean rethinking and changing ideas about white identity and reorienting the practices consequent upon these ideas.}}</ref> In biological examination, whiteness studies has sought to expose how \"white identity is neither pure nor unchanging \u2013 that its genealogy is mixed\" in order to unearth biases within the white racial identity.<ref>{{cite article|author1=Warren Hedges|title=White Men in the United States|chapter=|date=1995|publisher=[[Southern Oregon University]]|pages=|isbn=|quote=It also suggests that any change in images and understandings of white men in the culture will be tied to disassociating whiteness from objectivity and universality ... white identity is neither pure nor unchanging \u2013 that its genealogy is mixed}}</ref>\n\n===White privilege===\n{{main|White privilege}}\nIn 1965, drawing from insights from Du Bois and inspired by the Civil Rights Movement, [[Theodore W. Allen]] began a 40-year analysis of \"white skin privilege\", \"white race\" privilege, and \"white\" privilege. In a piece he drafted for a \"John Brown Commemoration Committee\", he urged that \"White Americans who want government of the people\" and \"by the people\" to \"begin by first repudiating their white skin privileges\".<ref>{{cite book | title =John Brown Memorial Pilgrimage | publisher = John Brown Commemoration Committee | date =  December 4, 1965}}</ref><ref name=\"Perry\" /><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Allen |display-authors=etal | title = July 2010 edition | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = July 2010 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2010/2010.html | ref = harv }}</ref> From 1967 to 1969 various versions of the pamphlet, \"White Blindspot\", containing pieces by Allen and Noel Ignatin ([[Noel Ignatiev]]), focused on the struggle against \"white skin privilege\" and significantly influenced [[Students for a Democratic Society]] (SDS) and sectors of the [[New Left]]. By June 15, 1969, ''The New York Times'' was reporting that the National Office of SDS was calling \"for an all-out fight against 'white skin privileges'\".<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Ignatin (Ignatiev) | first1 = Noel | last2 = Allen | first2 = Ted | chapter = White Blindspot | chapter-url = http://www.sds-1960s.org/WhiteBlindspot.pdf | editor-last = Davidson | editor-first = Carl | title = Revolutionary Youth & the New Working Class: the Praxis Papers, the Port Authority Statement, the RYM Documents and Other Lost Writings of SDS | pages = 148&ndash;181 | publisher = Changemaker Publications | location = Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania | year = 2011 | isbn = 9781257999477 }}\n:Reproduction of two pamphlets:\n:* {{cite book | last = Ignatin | first = Noel | title =Letter to Progressive Labor | url = http://www.sds-1960s.org/WhiteBlindspot.pdf | pages = 148&ndash;163 | location = New York |date=March 1967}}\n:* {{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = A Letter of Support | url = http://www.sds-1960s.org/WhiteBlindspot.pdf | pages = 163&ndash;167 | location = Brooklyn, New York |date=1967}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Brooks | first = Thomas R. | title = The New Left is Showing Its Age | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1969/06/15/archives/the-new-left-is-showing-its-age-the-new-left-is-showing-its-age.html | work = The New York Times | date = June 15, 1969 | page = 20}}</ref><ref name=\"Perry\" />\n\nIn 1974\u20131975, Allen extended his analysis of \"white privilege\", racial oppression, and social control to the colonial period with his ground-breaking ''Class Struggle and the Origin of Racial Slavery: The Invention of the White Race.''<ref name=\"Struggle\">{{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = Class Struggle and the Origin of Racial Slavery: The Invention of the White Race | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2006/allen.html |publisher= Center for the Study of Working Class Life, SUNY, Stony Brook | location = Stony Brook, NY |origyear=1975 |year=2006 | oclc = 244189582}} With an \"Introduction\" by Jeffrey B. Perry.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = Class Struggle and the Origin of Racial Slavery: The Invention of the White Race | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = 2006 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2006/allen.html | ref = harv }}</ref> With continued research, he developed his ideas as his seminal two-volume ''The Invention of the White Race'' published in 1994 and 1997.<ref name=\"Intervention_Vol_I\">{{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = The Invention of the White Race: Volume 1, Racial Oppression and Social Control | url = http://www.versobooks.com/books/1039-the-invention-of-the-white-race-volume-1 |publisher=Verso Books | location = London |origyear=1994 |year=2012| isbn = 9781844677696}}</ref><ref name=\"Intervention_Vol_II\">{{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = The Invention of the White Race: Volume 2, The Origin of Racial Oppression in Anglo-America | url = http://www.versobooks.com/books/1048-the-invention-of-the-white-race-volume-2 |publisher=Verso Books | location = London |origyear=1997 |year=2012| isbn = 9781844677702}}</ref>\n\nFor almost forty years, Allen offered a detailed historical analysis of the origin, maintenance, and functioning of \"white-skin privilege\" and \"white privilege\" in such writings as: \"White Supremacy in U.S. History\" (1973);<ref>Ted (Theodore W.) Allen, [http://www.sojournertruth.net/uafws.pdf \"White Supremacy in U.S. History\"], A Speech Delivered at a Guardian Forum on the National Question, 28 April 1973, rpt. in \"White Supremacy a Collection\" (Chicago: Sojourner Truth Organization, 1976;</ref> \"Class Struggle and the Origin of Racial Slavery: The Invention of the White Race\" (1975);<ref name=\"Struggle\" /> \"The Invention of the White Race,\" Vol. 1: \"Racial Oppression and Social Control\" (1994, 2012);<ref name=\"Intervention_Vol_I\" /> \"The Invention of the White Race,\" Vol. 2: \"The Origin of Racial Oppression in Anglo-America\" (1997, 2012);<ref name=\"Intervention_Vol_II\" /> \"Summary of the Argument of 'The Invention of the White Race'\" Parts 1<ref name=\"Summary_pt1\">{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = Summary of the Argument of 'The Invention of the White Race,'\" Part 1 | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 1 | issue = 2 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = Spring 1998 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/1-2/allen.html | ref = harv }}</ref> and 2<ref name=\"Summary_pt2\">{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = Summary of the Argument of 'The Invention of the White Race,'\" Part 2 | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 1 | issue = 2 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = Spring 1998 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/1-2/allen2.html | ref = harv }}</ref> (1998); \"In Defense of Affirmative Action in Employment Policy\" (1998);<ref>{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = In Defense of Affirmative Action in Employment Policy | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 1 | issue = 2 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = Spring 1998 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/1-2/affirmative.html | ref = harv }}</ref> \"'Race' and 'Ethnicity': History and the 2000 Census\" (1999);<ref>{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = 'Race' and 'Ethnicity': History and the 2000 Census | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 3 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = 2009 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/3-1&2/allen.html | ref = harv }}</ref> and \"On Roediger's Wages of Whiteness\" (Revised Edition)\";<ref name=\"Wages\">{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = On Roediger's ''Wages of Whiteness'' | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 4 | issue = 2 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = Spring 2001 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/4-2/allen.html | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nIn his historical work, Allen asserted that: \n*the \"white race\" was invented as a ruling class social control formation in the late 17th-/early-18th century Anglo-American [[plantations in the American South|plantation]] colonies (principally Virginia and Maryland); \n*central to this process was the ruling-class plantation bourgeoisie conferring \"white race\" privileges on European-American working people; \n*these privileges were not only against the interests of African Americans, they were also \"poison\", \"ruinous\", a baited hook, to the class interests of working people; \n*[[white supremacy]], reinforced by \"white skin privilege\", has been the main retardant of working-class consciousness in the US; and\n*struggle for radical social change should direct principal efforts at challenging white supremacy and \"white skin privileges\".<ref name=\"Perry\">{{cite journal | last = Perry | first = Jeffrey B. | title = The Developing Conjuncture and Insights from Hubert Harrison and Theodore W. Allen on the Centrality of the Fight Against White Supremacy | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = July 2010 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2010/2010.html | ref = harv }} [http://www.jeffreybperry.net/files/Perry.pdf Pdf.]</ref>{{rp|pp. 10\u201311, 34}} Allen's work influenced Students for a Democratic Society (SDS) and sectors of the \"new left\" and paved the way for \"white privilege\", \"race as social construct\", and \"whiteness studies\". He also raised important questions about developments in those areas, and he avoided using the term \"whiteness\", using quotation marks when he did.<ref name=\"Summary_pt1\" /><ref name=\"Perry\" />{{rp|pp. 8, 78 n. 187, 80\u201389}}\n\nLaura Pulido writes about the relation of white privilege to racism. \n<blockquote>\"White privilege [is] a highly structural and spatial form of racism&nbsp;... I suggest that historical processes of suburbanization and decentralization are instances of white privilege and have contributed to contemporary patterns of environmental racism.\"<ref name=\"pulido\"/></blockquote>Pulido defines [[environmental racism]] as \"the idea that nonwhites are disproportionately exposed to pollution\".<ref name=\"pulido\">{{cite journal | last = Pulido | first = Laura | title = Rethinking Environmental Racism: Whiteness Privilege and Urban Development in Southern California | journal = [[Annals of the Association of American Geographers]] | volume = 90 | issue = 1 | pages = 12\u201340 | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] | doi=10.1111/0004-5608.00182 | date = 2000 | ref = harv | url = https://atrium.lib.uoguelph.ca/xmlui/bitstream/10214/1833/1/30-Pulido.pdf | hdl = 10214/1833 }}\n</ref>\n\nWriters such as [[Peggy McIntosh]] say that social, political, and cultural advantages are accorded to whites in global society. She argues that these advantages seem invisible to white people, but obvious to non-whites. McIntosh argues that whites utilize their whiteness, consciously or unconsciously, as a framework to classify people and understand their social locations. In addition, even though many white people understand that whiteness is associated with privilege, they do not acknowledge their privilege because they view themselves as average and non-racist. Essentially, whiteness is invisible to white people.<ref name=\"mcintosh\">{{cite book | last = McIntosh | first = Peggy | author-link = Peggy McIntosh | chapter = White Privilege: Unpacking the Invisible Knapsack | editor-last = Rothenberg | editor-first = Paula S. | title = Race, Class, and Gender in the United States: An Integrated Study | pages = 188&ndash;192 | publisher = Worth Publishers/Macmillan Learning | location = New York | year = 2016 | edition = 10th | isbn = 9781464178665 }}</ref>\n\nFor instance, \n<blockquote>\"I think whites are carefully taught not to recognize white privilege, as males are taught not to recognize [[male privilege]]. So I have begun in an untouched way to ask what it is like to have white privilege. I have come to see white privilege as an invisible package of unearned assets which I can count on cashing in each day, but about which I was 'meant' to remain oblivious\" (188).<ref name=\"mcintosh\"/></blockquote>McIntosh calls for Americans to acknowledge white privilege so that they can more effectively attain [[Social equality|equality]] in American society. She argues, \n<blockquote>\"To redesign social systems we need first to acknowledge their colossal unseen dimensions. The silences and denials surrounding privilege are the key political tool here. They keep the thinking about equality or equity incomplete, protecting unearned advantage and conferred dominance by making these [[taboo]] subjects\" (192).<ref name=\"mcintosh\"/></blockquote>\n\nWhite privilege is also related to [[white guilt]]. As Shannon Jackson writes in the article, \"''White Noises: On Performing White, On Writing Performance''\" (1998), \"The rhetorics of white guilt are tiresome, cliche, disingenuous, and everywhere. And now that the stereotype of 'the guilty white' is almost entrenched in its negativity as 'the racist white', people actively try to dis-identify from both.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last = Jackson | first = Shannon | title = White Noises: On Performing White, On Writing Performance | journal = [[The Drama Review]] | volume = 42 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201365 | doi=10.1162/105420498760308670 | date = 1998 | publisher = [[MIT Press]] | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n===White shift===\n{{main|White shift}}\nWhite racial shift or decline, which has been abbreviated to the phrase whiteshift, and its intersection or connectedness to whiteness, has been a source of study and academic research within the field of whiteness studies. In relation to demographic decline of white people, the phenomenon has been analyzed as producing \"a formal re-articulation of whiteness as a social category\" in relation to fear-based politics with the US.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2008-may-19-oe-rodriguez19-story.html |title=The fear of white decline|author=Gregory Rodriquez |date=May 19, 2008|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|quote=Rather, it is a formal re-articulation of whiteness as a social category and a racial interest group. For decades now, scholars have been writing about the invisibility of whiteness. To be white in America meant that you were a member of the default category that just isn\u2019t discussed.}}</ref> Academic [[Vron Ware]] has examined this fear-based element in the sociology of resentment, and its intersection with class and whiteness. Ware analyzed how white decline, and its portrayal in [[British media]], facilitated a victim or grievance culture, particularly among [[white British]] working-class communities.<ref>{{Cite study|title=Towards a Sociology of Resentment: A Debate on Class and Whiteness |author=Vron Ware|authorlink=Vron Ware|date=December 11, 2017|publisher=[[Open University]]|quote=The concept of \u2018white decline\u2019 and the subsequent embracing of victim identity precipitates political formations that endanger fragile multicultures.}}</ref>\n\nPolitical scientist [[Charles King (professor of international affairs)|Charles King]] has proposed that, in the context of the numerical decline of [[white Americans]], whiteness is progressively revealed to be driven by social power, rather than biology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/22/us/white-americans-minority-population.html |title=Why the Announcement of a Looming White Minority Makes Demographers Nervous |author=Sabrina Tavernise|authorlink=Sabrina Tavernise|date=November 22, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|quote=That is because race is about power, not biology, said Charles King, a political science professor at Georgetown University. \u201cThe closer you get to social power, the closer you get to whiteness,\u201d said Dr. King, author of a coming book on [[Franz Boas]], the early 20th-century anthropologist who argued against theories of racial difference.}}</ref> Academic [[Eric Kaufmann]] has written that, while an \"unmixed whiteness\" is not likely to disappear altogether in Western nations, there is an ongoing demographic process of [[white shift]]; the numerical decline of whites, occurring simultaneously with non-whites joining white majorities through intermarriage and entering the social category of whiteness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quillette.com/2019/05/24/how-can-we-manage-the-process-of-western-whiteshift/ |title=How Can We Manage the Process of Western \u2018Whiteshift\u2019? |date=24 May 2019|publisher=[[Quillette]]|author=Eric Kaufmann|authorlink=Eric Kaufmann|quote=The challenge is to enable conservative whites to see a future for themselves in whiteshift \u2014 the mixture of many non-whites into the white group through voluntary assimilation. Unmixed whiteness is not about to disappear and may return in the long run.}}</ref>\n\n==Schools of thought==\n===Critical whiteness studies===\nAn offshoot of [[critical race theory]], theorists of '''critical whiteness studies''' seek to examine the construction and moral implications of whiteness, in order to reveal and deconstruct its assumed links to [[white privilege]] and [[white supremacy]]. Barbara Applebaum defines it as the \"field of scholarship whose aim is to reveal the invisible structures that produce and reproduce white supremacy and privilege\", and \"presumes a certain conception of racism that is connected to white supremacy\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Applebaum|first=Barbara|chapter=Critical Whiteness Studies|date=2016-06-09|url=https://oxfordre.com/education/view/10.1093/acrefore/9780190264093.001.0001/acrefore-9780190264093-e-5|encyclopedia=Oxford Research Encyclopedia of Education|publisher=Oxford University Press|language=en|doi=10.1093/acrefore/9780190264093.013.5|isbn=978-0-19-026409-3|access-date=2019-11-25|title=Oxford Research Encyclopedias: Education}}</ref> Anoop Nayak describes it as underpinned by the belief that whiteness is \"a modern invention [which] has changed over time and place\", \"a social norm and has become chained to an index of unspoken privileges\", and that \"the bonds of whiteness can yet be broken/deconstructed for the betterment of humanity\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nayak|first=Anoop|date=2007|title=Critical Whiteness Studies|journal=Sociology Compass|language=en|volume=1|issue=2|pages=737\u2013755|doi=10.1111/j.1751-9020.2007.00045.x|issn=1751-9020}}</ref> There is a great deal of overlap between critical whiteness studies and critical race theory, as demonstrated by focus on the legal and historical construction of white identity, and the use of narratives (whether legal discourse, testimony or fiction) as a tool for exposing systems of racial power.<ref>''See, for example'':\n* {{cite book | last = Haney-L\u00f3pez | first = Ian F. | title = White by law: the legal construction of race | publisher = New York University Press | location = New York | origyear = 1995 | year = 2006 | edition = 10th | isbn = 9780814753415 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Lipsitz | first = George | title = The Possessive Investment in Whiteness: How White People Profit from Identity Politics | publisher = Temple University Press | location = Philadelphia | origyear = 1998 | year = 2018 | edition = 20th | isbn = 9781439916407 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Delgado | first = Richard | author-link = Richard Delgado | title = Critical race theory: an introduction | publisher = New York University Press | location = New York | year = 2012 | isbn = 9780814721360 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Williams | first = Patricia J. | author-link = Patricia J. Williams | title = The Alchemy of Race and Rights: Diary of a Law Professor | publisher = Harvard University Press | location = Cambridge, Massachusetts | year = 1991 | isbn = 9780674014701 | title-link = The Alchemy of Race and Rights }}\n* {{cite book | last = Kovel | first = Joel | author-link = Joel Kovel | title = White racism: a psychohistory | publisher = Columbia University Press | location = New York | year = 1984 | isbn = 9780231057974 }}</ref>\n\n==Whiteness and architecture==\nIn the early 21st century, architectural historians have published studies related to the construction of whiteness in the built environment. Studies have grappled with the exclusionary nature of the architectural profession, which erected barriers for nonwhite practitioners, the ways in which architects and designers have employed motifs, art programs, and color schemes that reflected the aspirations of [[European Americans|European-Americans]] and, most recently, with the racialization of space.<ref>''For studies of whiteness and architecture, see'':\n* {{cite book | last = Berger | first = Martin A. | title = Sight Unseen: Whiteness and American Visual Culture | publisher = University of California Press | location = Berkeley | year = 2005 | isbn = 9780520931916 }}\n* {{cite book | editor-last1 = Harris | editor-first1 = Dianne | editor-last2 = Ruggles | editor-first2 = D. Fairchild | editor-link2 = D. Fairchild Ruggles | title = Sites Unseen: Landscape and Vision | publisher = University of Pittsburgh Press | location = Pittsburgh | year = 2007 | oclc = 941156157 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Lokko | first = Lesley N.N. | author-link = Lesley Lokko | title = White Papers, Black Marks: Architecture, Race, Culture | publisher = University of Minnesota Press | location = Minneapolis | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780816637768 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Saito | first = Leland | title = The Politics of Exclusion: The Failure of Race-Neutral Policies in Urban America | publisher = Stanford University Press | location = Stanford, California | year = 2009 | isbn = 9780804759304 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Trachtenberg | first = Alan | author-link = Alan Trachtenberg | title = The Incorporation of America: Culture and Society in the Gilded Age | publisher = Hill and Wang | location = New York | origyear = 1982 | year = 2007 | edition = 25th anniversary | isbn = 9780809058280 }}</ref>{{clarify|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Criticisms==\nWriters [[David Horowitz]] and Douglas Murray draw a distinction between whiteness studies and other analogous disciplines.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The madness of crowds : gender, race and identity|last=Murray|first=Douglas|publisher=|year=2019|isbn=978-1-63557-998-7|location=London|pages=124|oclc=1119529087}}</ref> Writes Horowitz, \"[[Black Studies|Black studies]] celebrates blackness, [[Chicano Studies|Chicano studies]] celebrates Chicanos, [[women's studies]] celebrates women, and white studies attacks white people as evil.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Fears | first = Darryl | title = Hue and Cry on 'Whiteness Studies' | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A14386-2003Jun19 | work = [[The Washington Post]] | date = 20 June 2003}}</ref> Dagmar R. Myslinska, an Adjunct Associate Professor of Law at [[Fordham University]], argues that whiteness studies overlooks the heterogeneity of whites' experience, be it due to class, immigrant status,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Myslinska|first1=Dagmar|title=Contemporary First-Generation European-Americans: The Unbearable 'Whiteness' of Being|journal=Tulane Law Review|date=2014|volume=88|url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=2222267|page=559|ssrn=2222267}}</ref> or geographical location.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Myslinska | first = Dagmar | title = Racist Racism: Complicating Whiteness Through the Privilege & Discrimination of Westerners in Japan | journal = Law Review |date=2014|volume=83|url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=2399984|page=1|ssrn=2399984 | ref = harv }}</ref> Alastair Bonnett argues that whiteness studies treated \"white\" culture as a homogenous and stable \"racial entity\" - for example, Bonnett observes that whiteness researchers in Britain argued that white British people lived in a homogenous \"white culture\" (which Bonnett observed was never clearly described), with the researchers completely ignoring British culture's regional diversity, despite having ample opportunity to study it.<ref>Bonnett, Alastair. \"Anti\u2010racism and the critique of \u2018white\u2019identities.\" Journal of Ethnic and Migration Studies 22, no. 1 (1996): 97-110.</ref>\n\n[[Barbara Kay]], a columnist for the ''[[National Post]]'', has sharply criticized whiteness studies, writing that it \"points to a new low in moral vacuity and civilizational [[Self-hatred|self-loathing]]\" and is an example of \"academic pusillanimity.\" According to Kay, whiteness studies \"cuts to the chase: It is all, and only, about white self-hate.\"<ref name=Kay1>{{cite news | last = Kay | first = Barbara | title = Blaming whitey | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090520052049/http://www.barbarakay.ca/archive/20060913whitey.html | url = http://www.barbarakay.ca/archive/20060913whitey.html | archive-date =  May 20, 2009 | work = National Post | date =  September 13, 2006 | access-date =  August 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nKay noted the leanings of the field by quoting Jeff Hitchcock, co-founder and executive director of the Center for the Study of White American Culture (CSWAC)<ref>{{cite web | title = Home page | url = http://www.euroamerican.org/ | website = euroamerican.org | publisher = Center for the Study of White American Culture (CSWAC)}}</ref> who stated in a 1998 speech:\n{{cquote|There is no crime that whiteness has not committed against people of colour.... We must blame whiteness for the continuing patterns today... which damage and prevent the humanity of those of us within it....We must blame whiteness for the continuing patterns today that deny the rights of those outside of whiteness and which damage and pervert the humanity of those of us within it.<ref name=Kay1/><ref>{{cite book | last = Hitchcock | first = Jeff | title = Decentering Whiteness | url = http://www.euroamerican.org/library/confarchive/NCOW3/Hitchcock-speech-NCOW3.pdf | publisher = Center for the Study of White American Culture (CSWAC) | date = 7 November 1998}} Speech given at the 3rd National Conference on Whiteness, [[University of Chicago]]</ref>}}\n\nRegarding whiteness studies (WS) more broadly, Kay wrote:\n<blockquote>WS teaches that if you are white, you are branded, literally in the flesh, with evidence of a kind of original sin. You can try to mitigate your evilness, but you can't eradicate it. The goal of WS is to entrench permanent race consciousness in everyone&nbsp;\u2014 eternal victimhood for nonwhites, eternal guilt for whites&nbsp;\u2014 and was most famously framed by WS chief guru, [[Noel Ignatiev]], former professor at [[Harvard University]] [''sic'', Ignatiev was a Ph.D. student and then a tutor at Harvard, but never a professor], now teaching at the [[Massachusetts College of Art]]: \"The key to solving the social problems of our age is to abolish the white race&nbsp;\u2014 in other words, to abolish the privileges of the white skin.\"<ref name=Kay1/>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn addition to such criticism in the mass media, whiteness studies has earned a mixed reception from academics in other fields. In 2001, historian [[Eric Arnesen]] wrote that \"whiteness has become a blank screen onto which those who claim to analyze it can project their own meanings\" and that the field \"suffers from a number of potentially fatal methodological and conceptual flaws.\"<ref name=\"arnesen\">{{cite journal | last = Arnesen | first = Eric | title = Whiteness and the Historian's Imagination | journal = International Labor and Working-Class History | volume = 60 | issue = 60 | pages = 3&ndash;32 | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | jstor = 27672732 | date = October 2001 | ref = harv | doi = 10.1017/S0147547901004380 }}</ref>  First, Arnesen writes that the core theses of whiteness studies\u2014that racial categories are arbitrary social constructs without definite biological basis, and that some white Americans benefit from racist discrimination of non-whites\u2014have been common wisdom in academia for many decades and are hardly as novel or controversial as whiteness studies scholars seem to believe. Additionally, Arnesen accuses whiteness studies scholars of sloppy thinking; of making claims not supported by their sources; of overstating supporting evidence and [[cherry picking]] to neglect contrary information.\n\nHe notes that a particular datum almost entirely ignored by whiteness studies scholars is religion, which has played a prominent role in conflicts among various American classes. He says that a type of \"keyword literalism\" persists in whiteness studies, where important words and phrases from primary sources are taken out of their historical context. Whiteness has so many different definitions that the word is \"nothing less than a moving target.\"<ref name=\"arnesen\"/> Arnesen notes that whiteness studies scholars are entirely on the [[Far-left politics|far left]] of the [[political spectrum]], and suggests that their apparent vitriol towards white Americans is due in part to white workers not fulfilling the predictions of [[Marxist theory]] that the [[proletariat]] would overcome racial, national and class distinctions to unite and overthrow [[capitalism]]. He cites, as an example, [[David Roediger]]\u2019s afterword to the seminal ''Wages of Whiteness'', which asserts that the book was written as a reaction to \"the appalling extent to which white male workers voted for [[Reaganism]] in the 1980s.\"<ref name=\"arnesen\"/> Arnesen argues that in the absence of supporting evidence, whiteness studies often rely on amateurish [[Freudian]] speculation about the motives of white people: \"The [[psychoanalysis]] of whiteness here differs from the 'talking cure' of Freudianism partly in its neglect of the speech of those under study.\" Without more accurate scholarship, Arnesen writes that \"it is time to retire whiteness for more precise historical categories and analytical tools.\"<ref name=\"arnesen\"/>\n\nIn 2002 historian [[Peter Kolchin]] offered a more positive assessment and declared that, at its best, whiteness studies has \"unfulfilled potential\" and offers a novel and valuable means of studying history.<ref name=\"kolchin\">{{cite journal | last = Kolchin | first = Peter | author-link = Peter Kolchin | title = Whiteness Studies: The New History of Race in America | journal = [[Journal of American History]] | volume = 89 | issue = 1 | pages = 154&ndash;173 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | jstor = 270078 | doi = 10.2307/2700788 | date = June 2002 | ref = harv }} [https://www.cwu.edu/diversity/sites/cts.cwu.edu.diversity/files/documents/whiteness.pdf Pdf.]</ref>  Particularly, he praises scholarship into the development of the ''concept'' of whiteness in the United States, and notes that the definition and implications of a white racial identity have shifted over the decades. Yet Kolchin describes a \"persistent sense of unease \" with certain aspects of whiteness studies. There is no consensus definition of whiteness, and thus the word is used in vague and contradictory ways, with some scholars even leaving the term undefined in their articles or essays.\"<ref name=\"kolchin\"/> Kolchin also objects to \"a persistent dualism evident in the work of the best whiteness studies authors,\" who often claim that whiteness is a social construct while also arguing, paradoxically, that whiteness is an \"omnipresent and unchanging\" reality existing independent of socialization.<ref name=\"kolchin\"/> Kolchin agrees that entering a post-racial paradigm might be beneficial for humanity, but he challenges the didactic tone of whiteness studies scholars who single out a white racial identification as negative, while praising a black or Asian self-identification. Scholars in whiteness studies sometimes seriously undermine their arguments by interpreting historical evidence independent of its broader context (e.g., Karen Brodkin's examination of American anti-semitism largely neglects its roots in European anti-semitism). Finally, Kolchin categorically rejects the argument\u2014common amongst many whiteness scholars\u2014that racism and whiteness are intrinsically and uniquely American, and he expresses concern at the \"belief in the moral emptiness of whiteness [...] there is a thin line between saying that whiteness is evil and saying that whites are evil.\"<ref name=\"kolchin\"/>\n\n[[Theodore W. Allen]], pioneering writer on \"white skin privilege\" and \"white privilege\" from the 1960s until his death in 2005, offered a critical review \"On Roediger\u2019s Wages of Whiteness\" (Revised Edition).<ref name=\"Wages\" /> He personally put \"whiteness\" in quotes because he shied away from using the term. As Allen explained, \n<blockquote>\"it\u2019s an abstract noun, it\u2019s an abstraction, it\u2019s an attribute of some people, it\u2019s not the role they play. And the white race is an actual objective thing. It\u2019s not anthropologic, it\u2019s a historically developed identity of European Americans and Anglo-Americans and so it has to be dealt with. It functions... in this history of ours and it has to be recognized as such. . . .to slough it off under the heading of \u2018whiteness,\u2019 to me seems to get away from the basic white race identity trauma.\"<ref name=\"Wages\" /><ref name=\"Perry\" />{{rp|pp. 78 n. 187}}</blockquote>In a scholarly debate with whiteness studies pioneer David Roediger, [[Eric Kaufmann]], a scholar of [[political demography]] and [[identity politics]] and the author of ''[[Whiteshift (book)|Whiteshift]]'' (which was criticised for defending [[white identity politics]]),<ref>{{cite web|author1=Isaac Chotiner|title=A Political Scientist Defends White Identity Politics |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/a-political-scientist-defends-white-identity-politics-eric-kaufmann-whiteshift-book|publisher=[[The New Yorker]] |date=April 30, 2019}}</ref> criticizes the field as a whole, arguing :<blockquote>\"White Studies suffers from a number of serious flaws which should lead us to question whether this approach can continue to advance the frontiers of knowledge in the wider sphere of ethnic and racial studies\".. These flaws include: 1) a constructivism which fails to recognise the cognitive and social processes that underpin social 'reality'; 2) an excessive emphasis on ethnic boundaries as opposed to ethnic narratives, thereby overstating the degree of malleability possible in ethnic identity; 3) a tacit belief in white [[exceptionalism]], which overemphasises the ideological character of whiteness and [[Deification|deifies]] whites; 4) an elision of dominant ethnicity and race; and 5) a threefold parochialism in terms of place, time horizon and the role of race in ethnic studies.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Kaufmann|first=Eric|date=June 1, 2006|title=The Dominant Ethnic Moment|journal=[[Ethnicities (journal)|Ethnicities]]|volume=6|issue=2|pages=231\u2013266|doi=10.1177/1468796806063754|issn=1468-7968|url=http://www.ssoar.info/ssoar/handle/document/23034}}</ref></blockquote>Kaufmann then proposes, as an alternative approach to the study of white identity, the emerging concept of \"dominant ethnicity\", using [[Anthony D. Smith]]'s definition of \"ethnic group\" as a \"named, imagined, human community, many of whose members believe in a myth of shared ancestry and place of origin.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=National Identity|last=Smith|first=Anthony D.|publisher=Penguin|year=1991|isbn=0-14-012565-5|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==List of courses==\n*''U.S. Race Theory & the Problem of Whiteness'', [[Arizona State University]].<ref name=\"washingtonpost2015\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[African American studies]]\n*[[Anti-racism]]\n*[[Anti-bias curriculum]]\n*[[Blanqueamiento]]\n*[[Casta]]\n*[[Critical race theory]]\n*[[Historical definitions of race]]\n*[[Identity politics]]\n*[[Postmodernism]]\n*[[Race (classification of human beings)|Race]], for a discussion of the biological concept of race and its applicability to the human population\n*''[[Raising Race Questions]]''\n*[[Social criticism]]\n*[[Social interpretations of race]]\n*[[White people]]\n*[[White privilege]]\n\n==References==\n<!-- ----------------------------------------------------------\n  See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for a\n  discussion of different citation methods and how to generate\n  footnotes using the <ref>, </ref> and  <reference /> tags\n----------------------------------------------------------- -->\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n\n=== Books ===\n* {{cite thesis|degree=PhD | last = Affeldt | first = Stefanie |date=2014|title=Consuming Whiteness: Australian Racism and the 'White Sugar' Campaign | url = http://www.lit-verlag.de/isbn/3-643-90569-7|publisher=[[University of Hamburg]]| isbn = 9783643905697}}\n* {{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = The Invention of the White Race: Volume 1, Racial Oppression and Social Control | url = http://www.versobooks.com/books/1039-the-invention-of-the-white-race-volume-1 |publisher=Verso Books | location = London |origyear=1994 |year=2012| isbn = 9781844677696}}\n* {{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = The Invention of the White Race: Volume 2, The Origin of Racial Oppression in Anglo-America | url = http://www.versobooks.com/books/1048-the-invention-of-the-white-race-volume-2 |publisher=Verso Books | location = London |origyear=1997 |year=2012| isbn = 9781844677702}}\n* {{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = Class Struggle and the Origin of Racial Slavery: The Invention of the White Race | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2006/allen.html |publisher= Center for the Study of Working Class Life, SUNY, Stony Brook | location = Stony Brook, NY |origyear=1975 |year=2006 | oclc = 244189582}} With an \"Introduction\" by Jeffrey B. Perry.\n* {{cite book | last = Anderson | first = Warwick | title = The Cultivation of Whiteness: Science, Health and Racial Destiny in Australia | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham | year = 2006 | isbn = 9780822338406 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Berger | first = Maurice | title = White lies: race and the myths of whiteness | publisher = Farrar, Straus, Giroux | location = New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 9780374527150 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Bonnett | first = Alastair | title = White Identities: Historical and International Perspectives | publisher = Routledge | location = Oxon England | year = 2014 | isbn = 9781315839608 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Rasmussen | first1 = Birgit Brander | last2 = Klinenberg | first2 = Eric | last3 = Nexica | first3 = Irene J. | last4 = Wray | first4 = Matt | title = The making and unmaking of whiteness | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham, North Carolina | year = 2001 | isbn = 9780822327400 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Bush | first = Melanie E.L. | title = Everyday Forms of Whiteness: Understanding Race in a \"Post-Racial\" World | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | location = Lanham, Maryland | year = 2011 | edition = 2nd | isbn = 9780742599994 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Bush | first = Melanie E.L. | title = Breaking the Code of Good Intentions: Everyday Forms of Whiteness | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | location = Lanham, Maryland | year = 2004 | isbn = 9780742528642 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Donaldson | first = Laura E. | title = Decolonizing Feminisms: Race, Gender and Empire | publisher = University of North Carolina Press | location = Chapel Hill | year = 1992 | isbn = 9780415092180 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Dyer | first = Richard | author-link = Richard Dyer | title = White | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | origyear = 1997 | year = 2017 | edition = 20th anniversary | isbn = 9781138683044 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Ewen | first1 = Elizabeth | last2 = Ewen | first2 = Stuart | title = Typecasting: On the Arts and Sciences of Human Inequality: A History of Dominant Ideas | publisher = Seven Stories Turnaround | location = New York London | year = 2008 | isbn = 9781583229491 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Garner | first = Steve | title = Whiteness: An Introduction | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 2007 | isbn = 9780415403641 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Hage | first = Ghassan | author-link = Ghassan Hage | title = White Nation: Fantasies of White Supremacy in a Multicultural Society | publisher = Taylor & Francis | location = Annandale, NSW | year = 2015 | isbn = 9781138131903 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Hale | first = Grace Elizabeth | title = Making Whiteness: The Culture of Segregation in the South 1890-1940 | publisher = Vintage Books | location = New York | year = 1998 | isbn = 9780307487933 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Hill | first = Mike | title = After Whiteness: Unmaking an American Majority | publisher = NYU Press | location = New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 9780814744598 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Hill | first = Mike | title = Whiteness: A Critical Reader | publisher = New York University Press | location = New York | year = 1997 | isbn = 9780814735459 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Hughey  | first = Matthew W. | author-link = Matthew Hughey | title = White Bound: Nationalists, Antiracists, and the Shared Meanings of Race | publisher = Stanford University Press | location = Stanford, California | year = 2012 | isbn = 9780804776950 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Hund | first1 = Wulf | last2 = Krikler | first2 = Jeremy | last3 = Roediger | first3 = David R. | title = Wages of Whiteness & Racist Symbolic Capital | publisher = Lit | location = Berlin M\u00fcnster | year = 2010 | isbn = 9783643109491 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Kaplan | first = E. Ann | title = Looking For the Other: Feminism, Film and the Imperial Gaze | publisher = Routledge | location = New York London | year = 1997 | isbn = 9780415910170 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Lipsitz | first = George | title = The Possessive Investment in Whiteness: How White People Profit from Identity Politics | publisher = Temple University Press | location = Philadelphia | origyear = 1998 | year = 2018 | edition = 20th anniversary | isbn = 9781439916407 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Lokko | first = Lesley N.N. | author-link = Lesley Lokko | title = White Papers, Black Marks: Architecture, Race, Culture | publisher = University of Minnesota Press | location = Minneapolis | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780816637768 }}\n* {{cite book | last = MacMullan | first = Terrance | title = Habits of Whiteness: A Pragmatist Reconstruction | publisher = Indiana University Press | location = Bloomington | year = 2009 | isbn = 9780253318138 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Moreton-Robinson | first = Aileen | title = Whitening Race: Essays in Social and Cultural Criticism | publisher = Aboriginal Studies Press | location = Canberra, ACT | year = 2004 | isbn = 9780855754655 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Painter | first = Nell Irvin | title = The History of White People | publisher = [[W. W. Norton & Company]] | location = New York and London | year = 2010 | isbn = 9780393049343 | title-link = The History of White People }}\n* {{cite book | last = Preston | first = John | title = Whiteness and Class in Education | publisher = [[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] | location = Dordrecht | year = 2009 | isbn = 9789048123070 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Roediger | first = David R. | author-link = David Roediger | title = The Wages of Whiteness: Race and the Making of the American Working Class | publisher = Verso | location = London New York | year = 2007 | isbn = 9781844671458 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Roediger | first = David R. | author-link = David Roediger | title = Black on White: Black Writers on What It Means to Be White | publisher = Schocken Books | location = New York | year = 1998 | isbn = 9780805241464 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Sashedri-Crooks | first = Kalpana | title = Desiring Whiteness: A Lacanian Analysis of Race | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780415192552 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Tullos | first = Allen | title = Habits of Industry: White Culture and the Transformation of the Carolina Piedmont | url = https://archive.org/details/habitsofindustry0000tull | url-access = registration | publisher = University of North Carolina Press | location = Chapel Hill | year = 1989 | isbn = 9780807842478 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Young | first = Robert | title = White Mythologies: Writing History and the West | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 2004 | edition = 2nd | isbn = 9780415311816 }}\n\n=== Book chapters ===\n* {{cite book | last = Carby | first = Hazel V. | author-link = Hazel Carby | chapter = White Woman Listen! Black Feminism and the Boudaries of Sisterhood | editor-last = Mirza | editor-first = Heidi | title = Black British Feminism: A Reader | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 1997 | isbn = 9780415152891 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Connor | first1 = Rachel | last2 = Crofts | first2 = Charlotte | chapter = Assuming White Identities: Racial and Gendered Looking Across the Literature / Media Divide | editor-last1 = Brown | editor-first1 = Heloise | editor-last2 = Gilkes | editor-first2 = Madi | editor-last3 = Kaloski-Naylor | editor-first3 = Ann | title = White?Women: Critical Perspectives on Race and Gender | publisher = Raw Nerve Books | location = York | year = 1999 | isbn = 9780953658503 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Davy | first = Kate | chapter = Outing Whiteness: A Feminist Lesbian Project | editor-last = Hill | editor-first = Mike | title = Whiteness: A Critical Reader | publisher = New York University Press | location = New York | year = 1997 | isbn = 9780814735459 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Ignatin (Ignatiev) | first1 = Noel | last2 = Allen | first2 = Ted | chapter = White Blindspot | chapter-url = http://www.sds-1960s.org/WhiteBlindspot.pdf | editor-last = Davidson | editor-first = Carl | title = Revolutionary Youth & the New Working Class: the Praxis Papers, the Port Authority Statement, the RYM Documents and Other Lost Writings of SDS | pages = 148&ndash;181 | publisher = Changemaker Publications | location = Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania | year = 2011 | isbn = 9781257999477 }}\n::Reproduction of two pamphlets:\n::* {{cite book | last = Ignatin | first = Noel | title =Letter to Progressive Labor | url = http://www.sds-1960s.org/WhiteBlindspot.pdf | pages = 148&ndash;163 | location = New York |date=March 1967}}\n::* {{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = A Letter of Support | url = http://www.sds-1960s.org/WhiteBlindspot.pdf | pages = 163&ndash;181 | location = Ann Arbor, Michigan |date=1967}}\n* {{cite book | last = Lott | first = Eric | chapter = The Whiteness of Film Noir | editor-last = Hill | editor-first = Mike | title = Whiteness: A Critical Reader | pages = 81&ndash;101 | publisher = New York University Press | location = New York | year = 1997 | isbn = 9780814735459 }}\n* {{cite book | last = McIntosh | first = Peggy | author-link = Peggy McIntosh | chapter = White Privilege: Unpacking the Invisible Knapsack | editor-last = Rothenberg | editor-first = Paula S. | title = Race, Class, and Gender in the United States: An Integrated Study | pages = 188&ndash;192 | publisher = Worth Publishers/Macmillan Learning | location = New York | year = 2016 | edition = 10th | isbn = 9781464178665 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Nishikawa | first = Kinohi | chapter = White | editor-last1 = Ostrom | editor-first1 = Hans | editor-last2 = Macey, Jr. | editor-first2 = J. David | title = The Greenwood Encyclopedia of African American Literature | chapter-url = https://archive.org/details/greenwoodencyclo0000ostr | chapter-url-access = registration | pages = 1725&ndash;1726 | publisher = Greenwood Press | location = Westport, Connecticut | year = 2005 | isbn = 9780313329777 }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Smitheram | first1 = Jan | last2 = Woodcock | first2 = Ian | chapter = Architecture, Whiteness and Terror Politics | editor-last1 = Loo | editor-first1 = Stephen | editor-last2 = Bartsch | editor-first2 = Katharine | title = Panorama to Paradise: Scopic Regimes in Architecture and Urban Theory, Proceedings of the 24th Annual Conference of the Society of Architectural Historians, Australia and New Zealand | pages = 1&ndash;12 | publisher = Society of Architectural Historians ([[SAHANZ]]), Australia New Zealand | location = Adelaide, South Australia | year = 2007 | isbn = 9781920927554 }} CD Rom publication.\n* {{cite book | last = Tatum | first = Beverly Daniel | author-link = Beverly Daniel Tatum | chapter = Defining Racism: 'Can We Talk?' | editor-last = Rothenberg | editor-first = Paula S. | title = Race, Class, and Gender in the United States: An Integrated Study | pages = 124&ndash;131 | publisher = Worth Publishers/Macmillan Learning | location = New York | year = 2016 | edition = 10th | isbn = 9781464178665 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Woodcock | first = Ian | chapter = Multicultural Melbourne: Four Fantasies of Whitespace | editor-last1 = Long | editor-first1 = Colin | editor-last2 = Shaw | editor-first2 = Kate | editor-last3 = Merlo | editor-first3 = Claire | editor-link2 = Kate Shaw | title = Suburban Fantasies: Melbourne Unmasked | pages = 84&ndash;106 | publisher = Australian Scholarly Publishing | location = Melbourne | year = 2005 | isbn = 9781740970907 }}\n\n=== Journal articles ===\n* {{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = On Roediger's ''Wages of Whiteness'' | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 4 | issue = 2 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = Spring 2001 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/4-2/allen.html  | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Arnesen | first = Eric | title = Whiteness and the Historian's Imagination | journal = International Labor and Working-Class History | volume = 60 | issue = 60 | pages = 3&ndash;32 | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | jstor = 27672732 | date = October 2001 | ref = harv | doi = 10.1017/S0147547901004380 }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Gaines | first = Jane | title = White Privilege and Looking Relations: Race and Gender in Feminist Film Theory | journal = Cultural Critique | volume = 4 | issue = 4 | pages = 59&ndash;79 | publisher = [[University of Minnesota Press]] | doi = 10.2307/1354334 | date = Autumn 1986 | ref = harv | jstor = 1354334 }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Harris | first = Cheryl I. | title = Whiteness as Property | journal = [[Harvard Law Review]] | volume = 106 | issue = 8 | pages = 1707&ndash;1791 | doi = 10.2307/1341787 | date = June 1993 | ref = harv | jstor = 1341787 }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Hartman | first = Andrew | title = The Rise and Fall of Whiteness Studies | journal = [[Race & Class]] | volume = 46 | issue = 2 | pages = 22&ndash;38 | publisher = [[SAGE Publishing|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/0306396804047723 | date = October 2004 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Keating | first = Ann Louise | title = Interrogating \"Whiteness,\" (De)Constructing \"Race\" | journal = [[College English]] | volume = 57 | issue = 8 | pages = 901&ndash;918 | publisher = [[National Council of Teachers of English]] (NCTE) | date = December 1995 | url = http://www.ncte.org/journals/ce/issues/v57-8 | ref = harv | doi = 10.2307/378620 | jstor = 378620 }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Kolchin | first = Peter | title = Whiteness Studies: The New History of Race in America | journal = [[Journal of American History]] | volume = 89 | issue = 1 | pages = 154&ndash;173 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | jstor = 270078 | doi = 10.2307/2700788 | date = June 2002 | ref = harv }} [https://www.cwu.edu/diversity/sites/cts.cwu.edu.diversity/files/documents/whiteness.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{cite journal | last = Perry | first = Jeffrey B. | title = The Developing Conjuncture and Insights from Hubert Harrison and Theodore W. Allen on the Centrality of the Fight Against White Supremacy | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = July 2010 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2010/2010.html | ref = harv }} [http://www.jeffreybperry.net/files/Perry.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{cite journal | last = Shohat | first = Ella | title = Gender and the Culture of Empire: Towards a Feminist Ethnography of the Cinema | journal = [[Quarterly Review of Film and Video]] | volume = 13 | issue = 1&ndash;3 | pages = 45&ndash;84 | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/10509209109361370 | date = 1991 | ref = harv }}\n\n=== Other ===\n* Allen, Theodore W. [http://www.sojournertruth.net/uafws.pdf \"White Supremacy in U.S. History\"]. Speech delivered at a Guardian Forum on the National Question, April 28, 1973, rpt. in \"White Supremacy a Collection\", Chicago: Sojourner Truth Organization, 1976.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nathanrtodd.netfirms.com/documents/Spanierman_Todd_Neville(2006)Whiteness_Bib.pdf Towards a Bibliography of Critical Whiteness Studies]\n* [http://www.acrawsa.org.au/ Australian Critical Race and Whiteness Studies Association]\n* [http://www.iconoclastic.net/eccw/index.html European-American Collaborative Challenging Whiteness]\n* [http://www.camelproductions.net ''Frederick Douglass and the White Negro (2008)''] - documentary on the African-American / Irish relationship\n\n{{White people}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whiteness Studies}}\n[[Category:Definition of racism controversy]]\n[[Category:Postmodernism]]\n[[Category:Critical race theory]]\n[[Category:Political theories]]\n[[Category:Politics and race]]\n[[Category:Post-structuralism]]\n[[Category:Social constructionism]]\n[[Category:Social justice]]\n[[Category:White culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{Over-coverage|region=the United States|date=November 2019}} {{More footnotes|date=December 2017}}\n\n'''Whiteness studies''' is the study of the structures that produce [[white privilege]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/14/books/noel-ignatiev-dead.html |title=Noel Ignatiev, 78, Persistent Voice Against White Privilege, Dies|authorlink=Neil Genzlinger|author=Neil Genzlinger|quote=\u201cHow the Irish Became White\u201d is among a group of books that have been foundational to what became known as whiteness studies, a field that examines the structures that produce white privilege.|date=November 14, 2019|work=[[New York Times]]}}</ref> the examination of what whiteness is when analyzed as a race, a culture, and a source of [[systemic racism]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2015/7/24/9023721/white-whiteness-race-identity |title=White people have a race \u2014 but everyone flips out when we talk about it|authorlink=|author=Jen\u00e9e Desmond-Harris|quote=Examining what whiteness is \u2014 analyzing it as a race, a culture, and a concept that has fueled racism \u2014 isn't new, particularly in academia.|date=July 24, 2015|publisher=[[Vox Media]]}}</ref> and the exploration of other [[social phenomena]] generated by the societal compositions, perceptions and group behaviours of [[white people]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2015/03/30/prof-receives-hate-mail-over-problem-of-whiteness/70697394/ |title=Professor gets hate mail over 'Problem of Whiteness' |authorlink=|author=Kaila White|quote=Academics and researchers have taught classes and published works on \"Whiteness\" and the field of \"critical Whiteness studies\" since the '90s. \"Whiteness\" is an academic term that refers not to race but to a multilayered concept: how whites are viewed by society, how they view themselves, and the implications of those perceptions, such as social norms and discrimination.|date=March 31, 2015|publisher=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> An [[interdisciplinary]] arena of inquiry that has developed beginning in the [[United States]] from [[white trash]] studies and [[Critical race theory|critical race studies]], particularly since the late 20th century.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kennedy|first=Tammie M.|last2=Middleton|first2=Joyce Irene|last3=Ratcliffe|first3=Krista|last4=Welch|first4=Kathleen Ethel|last5=Prendergast|first5=Catherine|last6=Shor|first6=Ira|last7=West|first7=Thomas R.|last8=Cushman|first8=Ellen|last9=Kendrick|first9=Michelle|last10=Albrecht|first10=Lisa|date=2005-10-01|title=Symposium: Whiteness Studies|journal=Rhetoric Review|volume=24|issue=4|pages=359\u2013402|doi=10.1207/s15327981rr2404_1|issn=0735-0198}}</ref> It is focused on what proponents{{Who|date=November 2019}} describe as the cultural, historical and sociological aspects of people identified as white, and the [[social construction]] of \"whiteness\" as an ideology tied to social status.\n\nPioneers in the field include [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] (\"Jefferson Davis as a Representative of Civilization\", 1890; ''[[Darkwater]]'', 1920), [[James Baldwin]] (''[[The Fire Next Time]]'', 1963), [[Theodore W. Allen]] (''The Invention of the White Race,'' 1976, expanded in 1995), [[Ruth Frankenberg]] (''White Women, Race Matters: The Social Construction of Whiteness'', 1993), author and literary critic [[Toni Morrison]] (''[[Playing in the Dark: Whiteness and the Literary Imagination]]'', 1992) and historian [[David Roediger]] (''The Wages of Whiteness'', 1991).\n\nBy the mid-1990s, numerous works across many disciplines analyzed whiteness, and it has since become a topic for academic courses, research and anthologies. Some syllabuses associate the dismantling of [[white supremacy]] as a stated aim in the understanding of whiteness,<ref name=\"washingtonpost2015\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/11/12/a-course-originally-called-the-problem-of-whiteness-returns-to-asu-as-racial-tensions-boil-over-on-campuses/ |title=A course originally called 'The Problem of Whiteness' returns to Arizona State|authorlink=|author=Yanan Wang|quote=The syllabus described Critical Whiteness Studies as a field \u201cconcerned with dismantling white supremacy in part by understanding how whiteness is socially constructed and experienced.\u201d|date=November 12, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref> while other sources view the field of study as primarily educational and exploratory, such as in questioning the objectivity of generations of works produced in intellectual spheres dominated by white scholars.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cjr.org/special_report/the-man-who-saw-himself.php |title=The Man Who Saw Himself|authorlink=|author=Matthew Shaer|quote=The field of \u201cWhiteness Studies,\u201d as it is often termed in academic circles, has existed for decades. Writers ... have looked at the way whiteness has evolved as an ideology and a construct. In doing so, they have called into question the supposed objectivity of the work of generations of straight, white, male scholars|date=December 1, 2015|work=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]}}</ref>\n\nA central tenet of whiteness studies is a reading of history and its effects on the present that is inspired by [[postmodernism]] and [[historicism]], in which the very concept of [[Racism|racial superiority]] is said to have been socially constructed in order to justify discrimination against non-whites. Since the 19th century, some writers have argued that the [[Phenotype|phenotypical]] significances attributed to specific races are without biological association, and that race is therefore not a valid biological concept.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://academic.udayton.edu/race/01race/race.htm|title=What is Race?|last=Randall|first=Vernellia R.|website=academic.udayton.edu|access-date=September 22, 2016}}</ref> Many scientists have demonstrated that racial theories are based upon an arbitrary clustering of phenotypical categories and [[customs]], and can overlook the problem of gradations between categories.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Obasogie|first1=Osagie|title=Return of the race myth?|journal=New Scientist|date= July 1, 2009|volume=203|issue=2715|pages=22\u201323|accessdate=|bibcode=2009NewSc.203...22O|doi=10.1016/S0262-4079(09)61767-X}}</ref> Thomas K. Nakayama and Robert L. Krizek write about whiteness as a \"strategic rhetoric,\" asserting, in the essay \"Whiteness: A Strategic Rhetoric\", that whiteness is a product of \"discursive formation\" and a \"rhetorical construction\". Nakayama and Krizek write, \"there is no 'true essence' to 'whiteness': there are only historically contingent constructions of that social location.\"<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Nakayama | first1 = Thomas K. | last2 = Krizek | first2 = Ro L.bert | title = Readings in Rhetorical Criticism | chapter = Whiteness: A Strategic Rhetoric | edition = 3 |editor = Carl Burgchardt | isbn = 978-1-891136-12-2| date = January 1, 2005 }}</ref> Nakayama and Krizek also suggest that by naming whiteness, one calls out its centrality and reveals its invisible, central position. Whiteness is considered normal and neutral, therefore, to name whiteness means that one identifies whiteness as a rhetorical construction that can be dissected to unearth its values and beliefs.\n\nMajor areas of research in whiteness studies include the nature of [[white privilege]] and white identity, the historical process by which a white [[Race (human categorization)|racial identity]] was created, the relation of culture to white identity, and possible processes of social change as they affect white identity.\n\n== Definitions of whiteness ==\nZeus Leonardo defines whiteness as \"a racial discourse, whereas the category \u2018white people\u2019 represents a socially constructed identity, usually based on\u00a0skin color\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leonardo|first=Zeus|date=March 2002|title=The Souls of White Folk: Critical pedagogy, whiteness studies, and globalization discourse|journal=Race Ethnicity and Education|volume=5|issue=1|pages=29\u201350|doi=10.1080/13613320120117180|issn=1361-3324}}</ref> Steve Garner notes that \"whiteness has no stable consensual meaning\" and that \"the meanings attached to 'race' are always time- and place-specific, part of each national racial regime\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Whiteness : an introduction|last=Garner, Steve, 1963-|date=2007|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-40363-4|location=London|oclc=80358978}}</ref>\n\n==Development of the field==\nStudies of whiteness as a unique identity could be said to begin among [[black people]], who needed to understand whiteness to survive, particularly in slave societies such as the American colonies and United States.<ref name=hooksRepresentations>[[bell hooks]], \"Representations of Whiteness in the Black Imagination\", ''Black Looks'' (1992); republished in Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998).</ref><ref name=Ganley>{{cite journal | last = Ganley | first = Toby | title = What's all this talk about whiteness? | journal = Dialogue | volume = 1 | issue = 2 | pages = 12&ndash;30 | publisher = [[University of Queensland]] | date = 2003 | url = http://www.polsis.uq.edu.au//dialogue/vol-1-2-4.pdf | ref = harv | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130428181555/http://www.polsis.uq.edu.au//dialogue/vol-1-2-4.pdf | archive-date = 2013-04-28 }} ([https://dialoguejournal.org.au/archives/ Link to journal.])</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Roediger | first = David | title = Critical studies of whiteness, USA: origins and arguments | journal = [[Theoria (sociology journal)|Theoria]] | volume = 48 | issue = 98 | pages = 72&ndash;98 | publisher = [[Berghahn Books|Berghahn]] | doi = 10.3167/004058101782485511 | date = 1 December 2001 | ref = harv }}</ref> An important theme in this literature is, beyond the general \"invisibility\" of blacks to whites, the unwillingness of white people to consider that black people study them anthropologically.<ref name=hooksRepresentations/> American author [[James Weldon Johnson]] wrote in his 1912 novel ''[[The Autobiography of an Ex-Colored Man]]'' that \"colored people of this country know and understand the white people better than the white people know and understand them\".<ref>[[James Weldon Johnson]], ''[http://etc.usf.edu/lit2go/64/the-autobiography-of-an-ex-colored-man/ The Autobiography of an Ex-Colored Man]'', Boston: Sherman, French, and Co., 2012; Chapter 2.</ref><ref>Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998), p. 5.</ref> Author [[James Baldwin]] wrote and spoke extensively about whiteness, defining it as a central social problem and insisting that it was choice, not a biological identity.<ref>Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998), pp. 20\u201321. \"No thinker so fully brought together the many dimensions of African-American studies of whiteness as James Baldwin. [...] Adopting and treasuring a white identity is, he wrote, 'absolutely a moral choice' since 'there are no white people.'\"</ref><ref>James Baldwin, \"On being 'white' and other lies\", ''Essence'', 1984; republished in Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998).</ref> In ''[[The Fire Next Time]]'' (1963), a non-fiction book on race relations in the United States, Baldwin suggests that \n<blockquote>\"White people in this country will have quite enough to do in learning how to accept and love themselves and each other, and when they have achieved this\u2014which will not be tomorrow and may very well be never\u2014the Negro problem will no longer exist, for it will no longer be needed.\"<ref>[[James Baldwin]], ''The Fire Next Time'', New York: Dial Press, 1963; republished in New York by Vintage International, 1993; p. 22.</ref></blockquote>A major black theory of whiteness connects this identity group with acts of [[terrorism]]\u2014i.e., slavery, rape, torture, and lynching\u2014against black people, who were treated as sub-human.<ref>Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998), pp. 15\u201316. \"Equally compelling African\u2013American studies treat whiteness as a species of terror. [...] [[Paul Gilroy]]'s recent ''The Black Atlantic'' uncompromisingly calls upon the tradition of connecting the terrors of the trade in black bodies, the bloodiness of slave control, and the soul-killing violence of racial exploitation with the total experience of whiteness by people of colors. [[bell hooks]] makes much the same points regarding the circumstances under which African Americans encounter and represent whiteness. Other black thinkers have carried this insight still further. They contend that whiteness is also experienced through terror by whites, who find and reproduce unity by committing and more often by witnessing acts of violence. Slave tales and autobiographies, for example, at times insisted upon the centrality of stealing humans, breaking up families, 'patrolling' plantations, and committing rape to the growth of a white identity.\"</ref>\n\nWhite academics in the United States and the United Kingdom (UK) began to study whiteness as early as 1983, creating the idea of a discipline called \"whiteness studies\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Murray | first = Albert | title = Omni-Americans: Some Alternatives to the Folklore of White Supremacy | publisher = Vintage | year = 1983 | oclc = 1020212158}}</ref> The \"[[canon wars]]\" of the late 1980s and 1990s, a political controversy over the centrality of white authors and perspectives in United States culture, led the scholar [[Shelley Fisher Fishkin]] to ask \"how the imaginative construction of 'whiteness' had shaped American literature and American history\".<ref name=\"Fishkin_interrogate\">{{cite journal | last = Fishkin | first = Shelley Fisher | author-link = Shelley Fisher Fishkin | title = Interrogating \"Whiteness,\" Complicating \"Blackness\": Remapping American Culture | journal = [[American Quarterly]] | volume = 47 | issue = 3 | pages = 428&ndash;466 | publisher = [[Johns Hopkins University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/2713296 | date = September 1995 | quote = In this essay I will provide a brief overview of over a hundred books and articles from fields including literary criticism, history, cultural studies, anthropology, popular culture, communication studies, music history, art history, dance history, humor studies, philosophy, linguistics, and folklore, all published between 1990 and 1995 or forthcoming shortly. Taken together, I believe, they mark the early 1990s as a defining moment in the study of American culture. | ref = harv | jstor = 2713296 | hdl = 2152/31168 }}</ref>{{rp|430}} The field developed a large body of work during the early 1990s, Fishkin describes it extending across the disciplines of \"literary criticism, history, cultural studies, sociology, anthropology, popular culture, communication studies, music history, art history, dance history, humor studies, philosophy, linguistics, and folklore\".<ref name=\"Fishkin_interrogate\" />\n\nAs of 2004, according to ''[[The Washington Post]]'', at least 30 institutions in the United States including [[Princeton University]], the [[University of California at Los Angeles]], the [[University of New Mexico]] and [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] offer, or have offered, courses in whiteness studies. Teaching and research around whiteness often overlap with research on [[post-colonial theory]] and [[orientalism]] taking place in the Arts and Humanities, Sociology, Literature, Communications, and Cultural and Media Studies faculties and departments, among others (e.g. Kent, Leeds). Also heavily engaged in whiteness studies are practitioners of [[anti-racism|anti-racist education]], such as [[Betita Martinez]] and the Challenging White Supremacy workshop.\n\nOne contribution to White Studies is [[Rich Benjamin]]'s ''[[Searching for Whitopia|Searching for Whitopia: An Improbable Journey to the Heart of White America]]''. The book examines white social beliefs and white anxiety in the contemporary United States\u2014in the context of enormous demographic, cultural, and social change.  The book is often taught as a primer in White Studies on white racial identity in a \"post-racial\" US.<ref>{{cite book | last = Benjamin | first = Rich | title = Searching for Whitopia: An Improbable Journey to the Heart of White America | publisher = Hyperion | location = New York | year = 2009 | isbn = 9781401322687 }}</ref>\n\nAnother major contribution to whiteness studies is the analysis of whiteness as a phenomenon, not just localized to the US and Western Hemisphere, but also in the context of other post-colonial metropoles such as the Netherlands.  [[Gloria Wekker]]\u2019s ''White Innocence: Paradoxes of Colonialism and Race'' excavates the immutability and fluidity of white identity and its relationship to innocence in the context of post-colonial [[Netherlands]] in the first decade of the twenty-first century. Wekker identifies white innocence as a contemporary construction and denial [aggressive national forgetting] of the Netherlands role and proximity to European imperialism, racial stratification and hierarchy, and its contributions to the making of contemporary constructions of national belonging and cultural normativity (autochtoon vs. allochtonen).\n\nIn Wekker\u2019s analysis, although a majority of the residents of the Netherlands are migrants, the process of stratifying Dutch from \u201cOther\u201d is facilitated through skin tone and non-Christian religious practices (\u201cdeviant\u201d, non-White religions). In Wekker's account, the process of racialization is reserved for mid-to-late twentieth century migrant groups [i.e. Muslims, Black Surinamese, Black Antilleans], interchangeably as a means of delineating groups outside the constructed immutable \u201cnorms\u201d of Dutch society. Ultimately, Wekker is illuminating the cultural and rhetorical maneuvering that occurs within Dutch popular culture, educational spaces, and national discourses that facilitate a normalizing, non-identity to whiteness and how this very concept is intricately connected to a longer historical nineteenth-century racial grammar that accompanied imperial expansion.<ref>{{cite book | last = Wekker | first = Gloria | title = White Innocence: Paradoxes of Colonialism and Race | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham | year = 2016 | isbn = 9780822360759 }}</ref>\n\n==Areas of study==\n===Whiteness===\nWhiteness studies draws on research into the definition of race, originating with the United States but applying to racial stratification worldwide. This research emphasizes the historically recent [[social construction]] of white identity. As stated by [[W. E. B. Du Bois]] in 1920: \"The discovery of a personal whiteness among the world's peoples is a very modern thing,\u2014a nineteenth and twentieth century matter, indeed.\"<ref>W. E. B. Du Bois, ''Darkwater'' (1920); republished in Roediger, ''Black on White'' (1998), p. 184.</ref> The discipline examines how white, Native, and African/black identities emerged in interaction with the institutions of slavery, colonial settlement, citizenship, and industrial labor. Scholars such as [[Winthrop Jordan]]<ref>{{cite book | last = Jordan | first = Winthrop D. | author-link = Winthrop Jordan | title = White over Black: American Attitudes Toward the Negro, 1550-1812 | publisher = Omohundro Institute of Early Armerian History and Culture, Wiliamsburg, Virginia | location = Chapel Hill | year = 2012 | edition = 2nd | isbn = 9781469600765 }}</ref> have traced the evolution of the legally defined line between \"blacks\" and \"whites\" to colonial government efforts to prevent cross-racial revolts among unpaid laborers.\n\nPrinceton professor [[Nell Irvin Painter]], in her 2010 book ''[[The History of White People]],''<ref>{{cite book | last = Painter | first = Nell Irvin | title = The History of White People | publisher = [[W. W. Norton & Company]] | location = New York and London | year = 2010 | isbn = 9780393049343 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/historyofwhitepe00pain }}</ref> says the idea of whiteness is not just a matter of biology but also includes \"concepts of labor, gender, class, and images of personal beauty\".(p. xi) The earliest European societies, including the Greeks and Romans, had no concept of race and classified people by ethnicity and social class, with the lowest class being slaves, most of whom were European in origin.(p. xi) Race science, developed in Europe in the 1800s, included intense analysis of different groups of Europeans, who were classified as belonging to three or four different races, with the most admirable being from northern Europe.(pp.&nbsp;215&ndash;6) From the early days of the United States, whiteness was a criterion for full citizenship and acceptance into society. The American definition of whiteness evolved over time; initially groups such as Jews and southern Europeans were not regarded as white, but as skin color became the primary criterion, they were gradually accepted. Painter argues that in the 21st century the definition of whiteness - or more precisely the definition of \"nonblackness\" - has continued to expand, so that now \"The dark of skin who happen to be rich ... and the light of skin from any (racial background) who are beautiful, are now well on their way to inclusion.\"(pp.&nbsp;389&ndash;90.)\n\nAcademic Joseph Pugliese is among writers who have applied whiteness studies to an [[Australia]]n context, discussing the ways that [[Indigenous Australians]] were marginalized in the wake of British colonization of Australia, as whiteness came to be defined as central to Australian identity, diminishing [[Aboriginal identity]] in the process.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Perera | first1 = Suvendrini | last2 = Pugliese | first2 = Joseph | title = White Law of the Biopolitical | journal = Journal of the European Association of Studies on Australia | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | pages = 87&ndash;100 | publisher = European Association of Studies on Australia | date = 2012 | url = http://www.easa-australianstudies.net/node/295 | ref = harv }} [http://www.easa-australianstudies.net/files/jeasa4spererajpugliese16.pdf Pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Perera | first1 = Suvendrini | last2 = Pugliese | first2 = Joseph | title = Death in a dry river: black life, white property, parched justice | journal = Somatechnics | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages = 65&ndash;86 | publisher = [[Edinburgh University Press]] | doi = 10.3366/soma.2011.0007 | date = 2011 | ref = harv }}</ref> Pugliese discusses the 20th-century [[White Australia policy]] as a conscious attempt to preserve the \"purity\" of whiteness in Australian society.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Pugliese | first = Joseph | title = Race as Category Crisis: Whiteness and the Topical Assignation of Race | journal = Social Semiotics | volume = 12 | issue = 2 | pages = 149&ndash;168 | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/103503302760212078 | date = 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Willard | first = Myra | title = History of the White Australia policy to 1920  |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofwhiteau0000will | url-access = registration | publisher = Frank Cass and Company | location = Carlton, Victoria  |origyear=1923 | year = 1967 | isbn = 9780714610368 }}</ref> Likewise Stefanie Affeldt considers whiteness \"a concept not yet fully developed at the time the first convicts and settlers arrived down under\" <ref>Affeldt, Stefanie. ''Consuming Whiteness'', p. 14.</ref> which, as a social relation, had to be negotiated and was driven forward in particular by the labour movement. Eventually, with the Federation of Australia, \"[o]verlaying social differences, the shared membership in the 'white race' was the catalyst for the consolidation of the Australian colonies as the Commonwealth of Australia\".<ref>Affeldt, Stefanie. ''Consuming Whiteness'', p. 15.</ref>\n\n===White backlash===\n{{main|White backlash}}\nWhite backlash or white rage in association with or as a consequence of whiteness is an area of investigation in whiteness studies. Sociologist [[Matthew Hughey]] has described this examination of racially-based backlash within its historical context; \"Another approach to the study of whiteness centres on the white \"back-lash\" against the advances born from the [[civil rights movement]].\"<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Matthew Hughey|author=Matthew Hughey|title=White Bound: Nationalists, Antiracists, and the Shared Meanings of Race|date=2012|publisher=[[Stanford University Press]]|pages=10|isbn=978-0804776950|chapter=Racists vs Antiracists?|quote=}}</ref>\n\nPolitical scientist [[Danielle Allen]] has analyzed the intersection of whiteness with North American demographic changes, stating how they can \"provoke resistance from those whose well-being, status and self-esteem are connected to historical privileges of 'whiteness'\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/donald-trumps-troubling-us-constituency-2015-9 |title=Trump is tapping into a troubling US constituency |authorlink=Danielle Allen|author=Danielle Allen|quote=|date=September 7, 2015 |work=[[Business Insider]]}}</ref> Discussing the method of this resistance, [[Veronica Strong-Boag]]'s co-edited ''Rethinking Canada: The Promise of Women's History'' explores how white backlash in Canada attempts to frames the defending of white interests as a \"defence of national identity\", rather than an acknowledgement of the political action of whiteness.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=|author=Mary-Jo Nadeau|editor1=Veronica Jane Strong-Boag|editor2=Mona Lee Gleason|editor3=Adele Perry|title=Rethinking Canada: The Promise of Women's History|date=2006|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|pages=389|isbn=978-0195431728|chapter=Who is Canadian Now?: Feminism and the Politics of Nation After. September 11|quote=A sense of insecurity, uncertainty and crisis fed a backlash to the gains made by minorities, a backlash which was not framed as an overt defence of whiteness, but rather, like the books described above, as a defence of national identity}}</ref>\n\nScholar [[George Yancy]] has explored the societal response to perceived loss of racial privilege in his 2018 book ''Backlash''; how reactions derived from whiteness fluctuate between [[Robin DiAngelo]]'s concept of [[white fragility]] versus the more extreme backlashes throughout history.<ref>{{cite book|title=Backlash: What Happens When We Talk Honestly about Racism in America|author1=George Yancy|authorlink1=George Yancy|quote=The responses that I received, however, speak to something more extreme than just reactionary or unreceptive responses. Rather than \"white fragility\", these responses are ones that speak to deep forms of white world-making|date=2018|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|location=|isbn=978-1538104057|page=50|edition=}}</ref>\n\n===White education===\nThe study of white education and its intersection with whiteness is a continuing area of research in whiteness studies. Scholarly investigation has critiqued white-derived education as inevitably for the benefit of, organized by, and oriented towards white people.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Maryemma Graham|editor2=Sharon Pineault-Burke|editor3=Marianna White Davis|authorlink=|author=Ann Louise Keating|title=Teaching African American Literature|chapter=\"Interrogating \"Whiteness,\" (De)Constructing \"Race\"|date=1998|publisher=[[Routledge]]|pages=195|isbn=978-0415916967|quote=At this early stage in own interrogation of \"whiteness\" I was tempted to draw on my African ancestry, disavow my \"white\" education, and entirely separate myself (intellectually, if not physically) from the so-called \"white race\". Interrogations of \"whiteness\" have had similar but far more extreme impact on my students.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2018/jan/23/the-toxicity-of-low-expectations-limits-indigenous-students|title=The toxicity of low expectations limits Indigenous students |edition=IndigenousX|authorlink=|author=Michelle Kerrin|quote=If you have been the token Indigenous student in your class, or if you have simply entered white education spaces, you may understand the complexities of having to negotiate your Indigenous identity in order to achieve the narrative of success.|date=January 23, 2018|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> [[Horace Mann Bond]] was one of the early scholars to identify bias and privilege operating in white education systems. Using his role as Secretary of the [[Massachusetts State Board of Education]] to promote universal public education in the US, Bond critiqued suggestions [[African Americans]] were not intelligent enough to participate in the same schools as [[white Americans]] and campaigned against calls for literacy tests for suffrage. He challenged the [[Southern Manifesto]] and identified bias for funding white education, rather than universal funding, even within the reformist movement for desegregated schools.<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=|author=Shelley Sallee|title=The Whiteness of Child Labor Reform in the New South|date=2004|publisher=[[University of Georgia Press]]|pages=106\u2013107|isbn=978-0820325705|chapter=Whiteness of Reform|quote=One reason references to literacy qualifications for suffrage remained an issue that shaped racialized rhetoric of reform was because competition for education funds was tight and reformers could use the idea that African Americans might surpass whites to bolster their case for creating funding for white education.}}</ref>\n\nWhiteness and privilege have continued in US education after [[Jim Crow laws|Jim Crow]] versions of the [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregationist]] ideology have lost their legitimacy due to legal and political failures.<ref>{{cite book | last = Irons | first = Jenny | chapter = Conclusion: Legitimacy, Whiteness, and Racism | chapter-url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0I5mA3Ui6ZQC&pg=PT199 | title = Reconstituting Whiteness: the Mississippi State Sovereignty Commission | pages = 198\u2013199 | publisher = Vanderbilt University Press | location = Nashville, Tennessee | year = 2010 | isbn = 9780826516855 }}</ref> Privacy and individualism discourses mask white fear and newer forms of exclusion in contemporary education according to scholar, Charles R. Lawrence III.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Lawrence | first = Charles R., III. | title = Forbidden Conversations: On Race, Privacy, and Community (A Continuing Conversation with John Ely on Racism and Democracy) | journal = Yale Law Journal | volume = 114 | issue = 6 | pages = 1359\u20131377 | jstor = 4135742 | date = 2005 | url = https://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/ylj/vol114/iss6/5 | ref = harv }} [https://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=4953&context=ylj Pdf.]</ref>\n\n===White identity===\n{{main|White identity}}\nAnalyzing whiteness to forge new understandings of white identity has been a field of exploration for academics since the publications which largely founded modern whiteness studies in the mid-1990s. In exploring [[Ruth Frankenberg]]'s works, and her interchanging use of the two concepts, the separation has been examined by scholars attempting to intellectually \"disengtangle each from the other\".<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ravi Malhotra|author2=Morgan Rowe|editor1=Leda M. Cooks|editor2=Jennifer S. Simpson|authorlink1=|authorlink2=|title=Whiteness, Pedagogy, Performance: Dis/Placing Race|chapter=Rowe and Malhotra|date=2007|publisher=[[Lexington Books]]|location=|isbn=978-0739114629|quote=Whiteness studies effectively demonstrate the connection between white identities and whiteness as a social construction, they do not reveal how we can disentangle each from the other ... The slippage between white identity and whiteness that occurs in Frankenberg's text is widespread, particularly within the foundational texts within the field of whiteness studies.}}</ref>\n\nSociologist [[Howard Winant]], favoring a deconstructionist (rather than abolitionist) study of whiteness, suggests this methodology can help redefine and reorient understanding of white identity.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Birgit Brander Rasmussen|editor2=Irene J. Nexica|editor3=Eric Klinenberg|editor4=Matt Wray|authorlink=Howard Winant|author=Howard Winant|title=The Making and Unmaking of Whiteness|chapter=Howard Winant|date=2001|publisher=[[Duke University Press]]|pages=107|isbn=978-0822327400|quote=I understand deconstructing whiteness to mean rethinking and changing ideas about white identity and reorienting the practices consequent upon these ideas.}}</ref> In biological examination, whiteness studies has sought to expose how \"white identity is neither pure nor unchanging \u2013 that its genealogy is mixed\" in order to unearth biases within the white racial identity.<ref>{{cite article|author1=Warren Hedges|title=White Men in the United States|chapter=|date=1995|publisher=[[Southern Oregon University]]|pages=|isbn=|quote=It also suggests that any change in images and understandings of white men in the culture will be tied to disassociating whiteness from objectivity and universality ... white identity is neither pure nor unchanging \u2013 that its genealogy is mixed}}</ref>\n\n===White privilege===\n{{main|White privilege}}\nIn 1965, drawing from insights from Du Bois and inspired by the Civil Rights Movement, [[Theodore W. Allen]] began a 40-year analysis of \"white skin privilege\", \"white race\" privilege, and \"white\" privilege. In a piece he drafted for a \"John Brown Commemoration Committee\", he urged that \"White Americans who want government of the people\" and \"by the people\" to \"begin by first repudiating their white skin privileges\".<ref>{{cite book | title =John Brown Memorial Pilgrimage | publisher = John Brown Commemoration Committee | date =  December 4, 1965}}</ref><ref name=\"Perry\" /><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Allen |display-authors=etal | title = July 2010 edition | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = July 2010 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2010/2010.html | ref = harv }}</ref> From 1967 to 1969 various versions of the pamphlet, \"White Blindspot\", containing pieces by Allen and Noel Ignatin ([[Noel Ignatiev]]), focused on the struggle against \"white skin privilege\" and significantly influenced [[Students for a Democratic Society]] (SDS) and sectors of the [[New Left]]. By June 15, 1969, ''The New York Times'' was reporting that the National Office of SDS was calling \"for an all-out fight against 'white skin privileges'\".<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Ignatin (Ignatiev) | first1 = Noel | last2 = Allen | first2 = Ted | chapter = White Blindspot | chapter-url = http://www.sds-1960s.org/WhiteBlindspot.pdf | editor-last = Davidson | editor-first = Carl | title = Revolutionary Youth & the New Working Class: the Praxis Papers, the Port Authority Statement, the RYM Documents and Other Lost Writings of SDS | pages = 148&ndash;181 | publisher = Changemaker Publications | location = Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania | year = 2011 | isbn = 9781257999477 }}\n:Reproduction of two pamphlets:\n:* {{cite book | last = Ignatin | first = Noel | title =Letter to Progressive Labor | url = http://www.sds-1960s.org/WhiteBlindspot.pdf | pages = 148&ndash;163 | location = New York |date=March 1967}}\n:* {{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = A Letter of Support | url = http://www.sds-1960s.org/WhiteBlindspot.pdf | pages = 163&ndash;167 | location = Brooklyn, New York |date=1967}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Brooks | first = Thomas R. | title = The New Left is Showing Its Age | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1969/06/15/archives/the-new-left-is-showing-its-age-the-new-left-is-showing-its-age.html | work = The New York Times | date = June 15, 1969 | page = 20}}</ref><ref name=\"Perry\" />\n\nIn 1974\u20131975, Allen extended his analysis of \"white privilege\", racial oppression, and social control to the colonial period with his ground-breaking ''Class Struggle and the Origin of Racial Slavery: The Invention of the White Race.''<ref name=\"Struggle\">{{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = Class Struggle and the Origin of Racial Slavery: The Invention of the White Race | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2006/allen.html |publisher= Center for the Study of Working Class Life, SUNY, Stony Brook | location = Stony Brook, NY |origyear=1975 |year=2006 | oclc = 244189582}} With an \"Introduction\" by Jeffrey B. Perry.</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = Class Struggle and the Origin of Racial Slavery: The Invention of the White Race | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = 2006 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2006/allen.html | ref = harv }}</ref> With continued research, he developed his ideas as his seminal two-volume ''The Invention of the White Race'' published in 1994 and 1997.<ref name=\"Intervention_Vol_I\">{{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = The Invention of the White Race: Volume 1, Racial Oppression and Social Control | url = http://www.versobooks.com/books/1039-the-invention-of-the-white-race-volume-1 |publisher=Verso Books | location = London |origyear=1994 |year=2012| isbn = 9781844677696}}</ref><ref name=\"Intervention_Vol_II\">{{cite book | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = The Invention of the White Race: Volume 2, The Origin of Racial Oppression in Anglo-America | url = http://www.versobooks.com/books/1048-the-invention-of-the-white-race-volume-2 |publisher=Verso Books | location = London |origyear=1997 |year=2012| isbn = 9781844677702}}</ref>\n\nFor almost forty years, Allen offered a detailed historical analysis of the origin, maintenance, and functioning of \"white-skin privilege\" and \"white privilege\" in such writings as: \"White Supremacy in U.S. History\" (1973);<ref>Ted (Theodore W.) Allen, [http://www.sojournertruth.net/uafws.pdf \"White Supremacy in U.S. History\"], A Speech Delivered at a Guardian Forum on the National Question, 28 April 1973, rpt. in \"White Supremacy a Collection\" (Chicago: Sojourner Truth Organization, 1976;</ref> \"Class Struggle and the Origin of Racial Slavery: The Invention of the White Race\" (1975);<ref name=\"Struggle\" /> \"The Invention of the White Race,\" Vol. 1: \"Racial Oppression and Social Control\" (1994, 2012);<ref name=\"Intervention_Vol_I\" /> \"The Invention of the White Race,\" Vol. 2: \"The Origin of Racial Oppression in Anglo-America\" (1997, 2012);<ref name=\"Intervention_Vol_II\" /> \"Summary of the Argument of 'The Invention of the White Race'\" Parts 1<ref name=\"Summary_pt1\">{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = Summary of the Argument of 'The Invention of the White Race,'\" Part 1 | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 1 | issue = 2 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = Spring 1998 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/1-2/allen.html | ref = harv }}</ref> and 2<ref name=\"Summary_pt2\">{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = Summary of the Argument of 'The Invention of the White Race,'\" Part 2 | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 1 | issue = 2 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = Spring 1998 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/1-2/allen2.html | ref = harv }}</ref> (1998); \"In Defense of Affirmative Action in Employment Policy\" (1998);<ref>{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = In Defense of Affirmative Action in Employment Policy | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 1 | issue = 2 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = Spring 1998 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/1-2/affirmative.html | ref = harv }}</ref> \"'Race' and 'Ethnicity': History and the 2000 Census\" (1999);<ref>{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = 'Race' and 'Ethnicity': History and the 2000 Census | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 3 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = 2009 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/3-1&2/allen.html | ref = harv }}</ref> and \"On Roediger's Wages of Whiteness\" (Revised Edition)\";<ref name=\"Wages\">{{cite journal | last = Allen | first = Theodore W. | title = On Roediger's ''Wages of Whiteness'' | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | volume = 4 | issue = 2 | pages =  | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = Spring 2001 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/4-2/allen.html | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nIn his historical work, Allen asserted that: \n*the \"white race\" was invented as a ruling class social control formation in the late 17th-/early-18th century Anglo-American [[plantations in the American South|plantation]] colonies (principally Virginia and Maryland); \n*central to this process was the ruling-class plantation bourgeoisie conferring \"white race\" privileges on European-American working people; \n*these privileges were not only against the interests of African Americans, they were also \"poison\", \"ruinous\", a baited hook, to the class interests of working people; \n*[[white supremacy]], reinforced by \"white skin privilege\", has been the main retardant of working-class consciousness in the US; and\n*struggle for radical social change should direct principal efforts at challenging white supremacy and \"white skin privileges\".<ref name=\"Perry\">{{cite journal | last = Perry | first = Jeffrey B. | title = The Developing Conjuncture and Insights from Hubert Harrison and Theodore W. Allen on the Centrality of the Fight Against White Supremacy | journal = Cultural Logic: Marxist Theory and Practice | publisher = Theodore W. Allen | date = July 2010 | url = http://clogic.eserver.org/2010/2010.html | ref = harv }} [http://www.jeffreybperry.net/files/Perry.pdf Pdf.]</ref>{{rp|pp. 10\u201311, 34}} Allen's work influenced Students for a Democratic Society (SDS) and sectors of the \"new left\" and paved the way for \"white privilege\", \"race as social construct\", and \"whiteness studies\". He also raised important questions about developments in those areas, and he avoided using the term \"whiteness\", using quotation marks when he did.<ref name=\"Summary_pt1\" /><ref name=\"Perry\" />{{rp|pp. 8, 78 n. 187, 80\u201389}}\n\nLaura Pulido writes about the relation of white privilege to racism. \n<blockquote>\"White privilege [is] a highly structural and spatial form of racism&nbsp;... I suggest that historical processes of suburbanization and decentralization are instances of white privilege and have contributed to contemporary patterns of environmental racism.\"<ref name=\"pulido\"/></blockquote>Pulido defines environmental racism as \"the idea that nonwhites are disproportionately exposed to pollution\".<ref name=\"pulido\">{{cite journal | last = Pulido | first = Laura | title = Rethinking Environmental Racism: Whiteness Privilege and Urban Development in Southern California | journal = [[Annals of the Association of American Geographers]] | volume = 90 | issue = 1 | pages = 12\u201340 | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] | doi=10.1111/0004-5608.00182 | date = 2000 | ref = harv | url = https://atrium.lib.uoguelph.ca/xmlui/bitstream/10214/1833/1/30-Pulido.pdf | hdl = 10214/1833 }}\n</ref>\n\nWriters such as [[Peggy McIntosh]] say that social, political, and cultural advantages are accorded to whites in global society. She argues that these advantages seem invisible to white people, but obvious to non-whites. McIntosh argues that whites utilize their whiteness, consciously or unconsciously, as a framework to classify people and understand their social locations. In addition, even though many white people understand that whiteness is associated with privilege, they do not acknowledge their privilege because they view themselves as average and non-racist. Essentially, whiteness is invisible to white people.<ref name=\"mcintosh\">{{cite book | last = McIntosh | first = Peggy | author-link = Peggy McIntosh | chapter = White Privilege: Unpacking the Invisible Knapsack | editor-last = Rothenberg | editor-first = Paula S. | title = Race, Class, and Gender in the United States: An Integrated Study | pages = 188&ndash;192 | publisher = Worth Publishers/Macmillan Learning | location = New York | year = 2016 | edition = 10th | isbn = 9781464178665 }}</ref>\n\nFor instance, \n<blockquote>\"I think whites are carefully taught not to recognize white privilege, as males are taught not to recognize [[male privilege]]. So I have begun in an untouched way to ask what it is like to have white privilege. I have come to see white privilege as an invisible package of unearned assets which I can count on cashing in each day, but about which I was 'meant' to remain oblivious\" (188).<ref name=\"mcintosh\"/></blockquote>McIntosh calls for Americans to acknowledge white privilege so that they can more effectively attain [[Social equality|equality]] in American society. She argues, \n<blockquote>\"To redesign social systems we need first to acknowledge their colossal unseen dimensions. The silences and denials surrounding privilege are the key political tool here. They keep the thinking about equality or equity incomplete, protecting unearned advantage and conferred dominance by making these [[taboo]] subjects\" (192).<ref name=\"mcintosh\"/></blockquote>\n\nWhite privilege is also related to [[white guilt]]. As Shannon Jackson writes in the article, \"''White Noises: On Performing White, On Writing Performance''\" (1998), \"The rhetorics of white guilt are tiresome, cliche, disingenuous, and everywhere. And now that the stereotype of 'the guilty white' is almost entrenched in its negativity as 'the racist white', people actively try to dis-identify from both.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last = Jackson | first = Shannon | title = White Noises: On Performing White, On Writing Performance | journal = [[The Drama Review]] | volume = 42 | issue = 1 | pages = 49\u201365 | doi=10.1162/105420498760308670 | date = 1998 | publisher = [[MIT Press]] | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n===White shift===\n{{main|White shift}}\nWhite racial shift or decline, which has been abbreviated to the phrase whiteshift, and its intersection or connectedness to whiteness, has been a source of study and academic research within the field of whiteness studies. In relation to demographic decline of white people, the phenomenon has been analyzed as producing \"a formal re-articulation of whiteness as a social category\" in relation to fear-based politics with the US.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2008-may-19-oe-rodriguez19-story.html |title=The fear of white decline|author=Gregory Rodriquez |date=May 19, 2008|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|quote=Rather, it is a formal re-articulation of whiteness as a social category and a racial interest group. For decades now, scholars have been writing about the invisibility of whiteness. To be white in America meant that you were a member of the default category that just isn\u2019t discussed.}}</ref> Academic [[Vron Ware]] has examined this fear-based element in the sociology of resentment, and its intersection with class and whiteness. Ware analyzed how white decline, and its portrayal in [[British media]], facilitated a victim or grievance culture, particularly among [[white British]] working-class communities.<ref>{{Cite study|title=Towards a Sociology of Resentment: A Debate on Class and Whiteness |author=Vron Ware|authorlink=Vron Ware|date=December 11, 2017|publisher=[[Open University]]|quote=The concept of \u2018white decline\u2019 and the subsequent embracing of victim identity precipitates political formations that endanger fragile multicultures.}}</ref>\n\nPolitical scientist [[Charles King (professor of international affairs)|Charles King]] has proposed that, in the context of the numerical decline of [[white Americans]], whiteness is progressively revealed to be driven by social power, rather than biology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/22/us/white-americans-minority-population.html |title=Why the Announcement of a Looming White Minority Makes Demographers Nervous |author=Sabrina Tavernise|authorlink=Sabrina Tavernise|date=November 22, 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|quote=That is because race is about power, not biology, said Charles King, a political science professor at Georgetown University. \u201cThe closer you get to social power, the closer you get to whiteness,\u201d said Dr. King, author of a coming book on [[Franz Boas]], the early 20th-century anthropologist who argued against theories of racial difference.}}</ref> Academic [[Eric Kaufmann]] has written that, while an \"unmixed whiteness\" is not likely to disappear altogether in Western nations, there is an ongoing demographic process of [[white shift]]; the numerical decline of whites, occurring simultaneously with non-whites joining white majorities through intermarriage and entering the social category of whiteness.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://quillette.com/2019/05/24/how-can-we-manage-the-process-of-western-whiteshift/ |title=How Can We Manage the Process of Western \u2018Whiteshift\u2019? |date=24 May 2019|publisher=[[Quillette]]|author=Eric Kaufmann|authorlink=Eric Kaufmann|quote=The challenge is to enable conservative whites to see a future for themselves in whiteshift \u2014 the mixture of many non-whites into the white group through voluntary assimilation. Unmixed whiteness is not about to disappear and may return in the long run.}}</ref>\n\n==Schools of thought==\n===Critical whiteness studies===\nAn offshoot of [[critical race theory]], theorists of '''critical whiteness studies''' seek to examine the construction and moral implications of whiteness, in order to reveal and deconstruct its assumed links to [[white privilege]] and [[white supremacy]]. Barbara Applebaum defines it as the \"field of scholarship whose aim is to reveal the invisible structures that produce and reproduce white supremacy and privilege\", and \"presumes a certain conception of racism that is connected to white supremacy\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Applebaum|first=Barbara|chapter=Critical Whiteness Studies|date=2016-06-09|url=https://oxfordre.com/education/view/10.1093/acrefore/9780190264093.001.0001/acrefore-9780190264093-e-5|encyclopedia=Oxford Research Encyclopedia of Education|publisher=Oxford University Press|language=en|doi=10.1093/acrefore/9780190264093.013.5|isbn=978-0-19-026409-3|access-date=2019-11-25|title=Oxford Research Encyclopedias: Education}}</ref> Anoop Nayak describes it as underpinned by the belief that whiteness is \"a modern invention [which] has changed over time and place\", \"a social norm and has become chained to an index of unspoken privileges\", and that \"the bonds of whiteness can yet be broken/deconstructed for the betterment of humanity\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Nayak|first=Anoop|date=2007|title=Critical Whiteness Studies|journal=Sociology Compass|language=en|volume=1|issue=2|pages=737\u2013755|doi=10.1111/j.1751-9020.2007.00045.x|issn=1751-9020}}</ref> There is a great deal of overlap between critical whiteness studies and critical race theory, as demonstrated by focus on the legal and historical construction of white identity, and the use of narratives (whether legal discourse, testimony or fiction) as a tool for exposing systems of racial power.<ref>''See, for example'':\n* {{cite book | last = Haney-L\u00f3pez | first = Ian F. | title = White by law: the legal construction of race | publisher = New York University Press | location = New York | origyear = 1995 | year = 2006 | edition = 10th | isbn = 9780814753415 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Lipsitz | first = George | title = The Possessive Investment in Whiteness: How White People Profit from Identity Politics | publisher = Temple University Press | location = Philadelphia | origyear = 1998 | year = 2018 | edition = 20th | isbn = 9781439916407 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Delgado | first = Richard | author-link = Richard Delgado | title = Critical race theory: an introduction | publisher = New York University Press | location = New York | year = 2012 | isbn = 9780814721360 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Williams | first = Patricia J. | author-link = Patricia J. Williams | title = The Alchemy of Race and Rights: Diary of a Law Professor | publisher = Harvard University Press | location = Cambridge, Massachusetts | year = 1991 | isbn = 9780674014701 | title-link = The Alchemy of Race and Rights }}\n* {{cite book | last = Kovel | first = Joel | author-link = Joel Kovel | title = White racism: a psychohistory | publisher = Columbia University Press | location = New York | year = 1984 | isbn = 9780231057974 }}</ref>\n\n==Whiteness and architecture==\nIn the early 21st century, architectural historians have published studies related to the construction of whiteness in the built environment. Studies have grappled with the exclusionary nature of the architectural profession, which erected barriers for nonwhite practitioners, the ways in which architects and designers have employed motifs, art programs, and color schemes that reflected the aspirations of [[European Americans|European-Americans]] and, most recently, with the racialization of space.<ref>''For studies of whiteness and architecture, see'':\n* {{cite book | last = Berger | first = Martin A. | title = Sight Unseen: Whiteness and American Visual Culture | publisher = University of California Press | location = Berkeley | year = 2005 | isbn = 9780520931916 }}\n* {{cite book | editor-last1 = Harris | editor-first1 = Dianne | editor-last2 = Ruggles | editor-first2 = D. Fairchild | editor-link2 = D. Fairchild Ruggles | title = Sites Unseen: Landscape and Vision | publisher = University of Pittsburgh Press | location = Pittsburgh | year = 2007 | oclc = 941156157 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Lokko | first = Lesley N.N. | author-link = Lesley Lokko | title = White Papers, Black Marks: Architecture, Race, Culture | publisher = University of Minnesota Press | location = Minneapolis | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780816637768 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Saito | first = Leland | title = The Politics of Exclusion: The Failure of Race-Neutral Policies in Urban America | publisher = Stanford University Press | location = Stanford, California | year = 2009 | isbn = 9780804759304 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Trachtenberg | first = Alan | author-link = Alan Trachtenberg | title = The Incorporation of America: Culture and Society in the Gilded Age | publisher = Hill and Wang | location = New York | origyear = 1982 | year = 2007 | edition = 25th anniversary | isbn = 9780809058280 }}</ref>{{clarify|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Criticisms==\nWriters [[David Horowitz]] and Douglas Murray draw a distinction between whiteness studies and other analogous disciplines.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The madness of crowds : gender, race and identity|last=Murray|first=Douglas|publisher=|year=2019|isbn=978-1-63557-998-7|location=London|pages=124|oclc=1119529087}}</ref> Writes Horowitz, \"[[Black Studies|Black studies]] celebrates blackness, [[Chicano Studies|Chicano studies]] celebrates Chicanos, [[women's studies]] celebrates women, and white studies attacks white people as evil.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Fears | first = Darryl | title = Hue and Cry on 'Whiteness Studies' | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A14386-2003Jun19 | work = [[The Washington Post]] | date = 20 June 2003}}</ref> Dagmar R. Myslinska, an Adjunct Associate Professor of Law at [[Fordham University]], argues that whiteness studies overlooks the heterogeneity of whites' experience, be it due to class, immigrant status,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Myslinska|first1=Dagmar|title=Contemporary First-Generation European-Americans: The Unbearable 'Whiteness' of Being|journal=Tulane Law Review|date=2014|volume=88|url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=2222267|page=559|ssrn=2222267}}</ref> or geographical location.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Myslinska | first = Dagmar | title = Racist Racism: Complicating Whiteness Through the Privilege & Discrimination of Westerners in Japan | journal = Law Review |date=2014|volume=83|url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=2399984|page=1|ssrn=2399984 | ref = harv }}</ref> Alastair Bonnett argues that whiteness studies treated \"white\" culture as a homogenous and stable \"racial entity\" - for example, Bonnett observes that whiteness researchers in Britain argued that white British people lived in a homogenous \"white culture\" (which Bonnett observed was never clearly described), with the researchers completely ignoring British culture's regional diversity, despite having ample opportunity to study it.<ref>Bonnett, Alastair. \"Anti\u2010racism and the critique of \u2018white\u2019identities.\" Journal of Ethnic and Migration Studies 22, no. 1 (1996): 97-110.</ref>\n\n[[Barbara Kay]], a columnist for the ''[[National Post]]'', has sharply criticized whiteness studies, writing that it \"points to a new low in moral vacuity and civilizational [[Self-hatred|self-loathing]]\" and is an example of \"academic pusillanimity.\" According to Kay, whiteness studies \"cuts to the chase: It is all, and only, about white self-hate.\"<ref name=Kay1>{{cite news | last = Kay | first = Barbara | title = Blaming whitey | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090520052049/http://www.barbarakay.ca/archive/20060913whitey.html | url = http://www.barbarakay.ca/archive/20060913whitey.html | archive-date =  May 20, 2009 | work = National Post | date =  September 13, 2006 | access-date =  August 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nKay noted the leanings of the field by quoting Jeff Hitchcock, co-founder and executive director of the Center for the Study of White American Culture (CSWAC)<ref>{{cite web | title = Home page | url = http://www.euroamerican.org/ | website = euroamerican.org | publisher = Center for the Study of White American Culture (CSWAC)}}</ref> who stated in a 1998 speech:\n{{cquote|There is no crime that whiteness has not committed against people of colour.... We must blame whiteness for the continuing patterns today... which damage and prevent the humanity of those of us within it....We must blame whiteness for the continuing patterns today that deny the rights of those outside of whiteness and which damage and pervert the humanity of those of us within it.<ref name=Kay1/><ref>{{cite book | last = Hitchcock | first = Jeff | title = Decentering Whiteness | url = http://www.euroamerican.org/library/confarchive/NCOW3/Hitchcock-speech-NCOW3.pdf | publisher = Center for the Study of White American Culture (CSWAC) | date = 7 November 1998}} Speech given at the 3rd National Conference on Whiteness, [[University of Chicago]]</ref>}}\n\nRegarding whiteness studies (WS) more broadly, Kay wrote:\n<blockquote>WS teaches that if you are white, you are branded, literally in the flesh, with evidence of a kind of original sin. You can try to mitigate your evilness, but you can't eradicate it. The goal of WS is to entrench permanent race consciousness in everyone&nbsp;\u2014 eternal victimhood for nonwhites, eternal guilt for whites&nbsp;\u2014 and was most famously framed by WS chief guru, [[Noel Ignatiev]], former professor at [[Harvard University]] [''sic'', Ignatiev was a Ph.D. student and then a tutor at Harvard, but never a professor], now teaching at the [[Massachusetts College of Art]]: \"The key to solving the social problems of our age is to abolish the white race&nbsp;\u2014 in other words, to abolish the privileges of the white skin.\"<ref name=Kay1/>\n</blockquote>\n\nIn addition to such criticism in the mass media, whiteness studies has earned a mixed reception from academics in other fields. In 2001, historian [[Eric Arnesen]] wrote that \"whiteness has become a blank screen onto which those who claim to analyze it can project their own meanings\" and that the field \"suffers from a number of potentially fatal methodological and conceptual flaws.\"<ref name=\"arnesen\">{{cite journal | last = Arnesen | first = Eric | title = Whiteness and the Historian's Imagination | journal = International Labor and Working-Class History | volume = 60 | issue = 60 | pages = 3&ndash;32 | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | jstor = 27672732 | date = October 2001 | ref = harv | doi = 10.1017/S0147547901004380 }}</ref>  First, Arnesen writes that the core theses of whiteness studies\u2014that racial categories are arbitrary social constructs without definite biological basis, and that some white Americans benefit from racist discrimination of non-whites\u2014have been common wisdom in academia for many decades and are hardly as novel or controversial as whiteness studies scholars seem to believe. Additionally, Arnesen accuses whiteness studies scholars of sloppy thinking; of making claims not supported by their sources; of overstating supporting evidence and [[cherry picking]] to neglect contrary information.\n\nHe notes that a particular datum almost entirely ignored by whiteness studies scholars is religion, which has played a prominent role in conflicts among various American classes. He says that a type of \"keyword literalism\" persists in whiteness studies, where important words and phrases from primary sources are taken out of their historical context. Whiteness has so many different definitions that the word is \"nothing less than a moving target.\"<ref name=\"arnesen\"/> Arnesen notes that whiteness studies scholars are entirely on the [[Far-left politics|far left]] of the [[political spectrum]], and suggests that their apparent vitriol towards white Americans is due in part to white workers not fulfilling the predictions of [[Marxist theory]] that the [[proletariat]] would overcome racial, national and class distinctions to unite and overthrow [[capitalism]]. He cites, as an example, [[David Roediger]]\u2019s afterword to the seminal ''Wages of Whiteness'', which asserts that the book was written as a reaction to \"the appalling extent to which white male workers voted for [[Reaganism]] in the 1980s.\"<ref name=\"arnesen\"/> Arnesen argues that in the absence of supporting evidence, whiteness studies often rely on amateurish [[Freudian]] speculation about the motives of white people: \"The [[psychoanalysis]] of whiteness here differs from the 'talking cure' of Freudianism partly in its neglect of the speech of those under study.\" Without more accurate scholarship, Arnesen writes that \"it is time to retire whiteness for more precise historical categories and analytical tools.\"<ref name=\"arnesen\"/>\n\nIn 2002 historian [[Peter Kolchin]] offered a more positive assessment and declared that, at its best, whiteness studies has \"unfulfilled potential\" and offers a novel and valuable means of studying history.<ref name=\"kolchin\">{{cite journal | last = Kolchin | first = Peter | author-link = Peter Kolchin | title = Whiteness Studies: The New History of Race in America | journal = [[Journal of American History]] | volume = 89 | issue = 1 | pages = 154&ndash;173 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | jstor = 270078 | doi = 10.2307/2700788 | date = June 2002 | ref = harv }} [https://www.cwu.edu/diversity/sites/cts.cwu.edu.diversity/files/documents/whiteness.pdf Pdf.]</ref>  Particularly, he praises scholarship into the development of the ''concept'' of whiteness in the United States, and notes that the definition and implications of a white racial identity have shifted over the decades. Yet Kolchin describes a \"persistent sense of unease \" with certain aspects of whiteness studies. There is no consensus definition of whiteness, and thus the word is used in vague and contradictory ways, with some scholars even leaving the term undefined in their articles or essays.\"<ref name=\"kolchin\"/> Kolchin also objects to \"a persistent dualism evident in the work of the best whiteness studies authors,\" who often claim that whiteness is a social construct while also arguing, paradoxically, that whiteness is an \"omnipresent and unchanging\" reality existing independent of socialization.<ref name=\"kolchin\"/> Kolchin agrees that entering a post-racial paradigm might be beneficial for humanity, but he challenges the didactic tone of whiteness studies scholars who single out a white racial identification as negative, while praising a black or Asian self-identification. Scholars in whiteness studies sometimes seriously undermine their arguments by interpreting historical evidence independent of its broader context (e.g., Karen Brodkin's examination of American anti-semitism largely neglects its roots in European anti-semitism). Finally, Kolchin categorically rejects the argument\u2014common amongst many whiteness scholars\u2014that racism and whiteness are intrinsically and uniquely American, and he expresses concern at the \"belief in the moral emptiness of whiteness [...] there is a thin line between saying that whiteness is evil and saying that whites are evil.\"<ref name=\"kolchin\"/>\n\n[[Theodore W. Allen]], pioneering writer on \"white skin privilege\" and \"white privilege\" from the 1960s until his death in 2005, offered a critical review \"On Roediger\u2019s Wages of Whiteness\" (Revised Edition).<ref name=\"Wages\" /> He personally put \"whiteness\" in quotes because he shied away from using the term. As Allen explained, \n<blockquote>\"it\u2019s an abstract noun, it\u2019s an abstraction, it\u2019s an attribute of some people, it\u2019s not the role they play. And the white race is an actual objective thing. It\u2019s not anthropologic, it\u2019s a historically developed identity of European Americans and Anglo-Americans and so it has to be dealt with. It functions... in this history of ours and it has to be recognized as such. . . .to slough it off under the heading of \u2018whiteness,\u2019 to me seems to get away from the basic white race identity trauma.\"<ref name=\"Wages\" /><ref name=\"Perry\" />{{rp|pp. 78 n. 187}}</blockquote>In a scholarly debate with whiteness studies pioneer David Roediger, [[Eric Kaufmann]], a scholar of [[political demography]] and [[identity politics]] and the author of ''[[Whiteshift (book)|Whiteshift]]'' (which was criticised for defending [[white identity politics]]),<ref>{{cite web|author1=Isaac Chotiner|title=A Political Scientist Defends White Identity Politics |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/q-and-a/a-political-scientist-defends-white-identity-politics-eric-kaufmann-whiteshift-book|publisher=[[The New Yorker]] |date=April 30, 2019}}</ref> criticizes the field as a whole, arguing :<blockquote>\"White Studies suffers from a number of serious flaws which should lead us to question whether this approach can continue to advance the frontiers of knowledge in the wider sphere of ethnic and racial studies\".. These flaws include: 1) a constructivism which fails to recognise the cognitive and social processes that underpin social 'reality'; 2) an excessive emphasis on ethnic boundaries as opposed to ethnic narratives, thereby overstating the degree of malleability possible in ethnic identity; 3) a tacit belief in white [[exceptionalism]], which overemphasises the ideological character of whiteness and [[Deification|deifies]] whites; 4) an elision of dominant ethnicity and race; and 5) a threefold parochialism in terms of place, time horizon and the role of race in ethnic studies.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Kaufmann|first=Eric|date=June 1, 2006|title=The Dominant Ethnic Moment|journal=[[Ethnicities (journal)|Ethnicities]]|volume=6|issue=2|pages=231\u2013266|doi=10.1177/1468796806063754|issn=1468-7968|url=http://www.ssoar.info/ssoar/handle/document/23034}}</ref></blockquote>Kaufmann then proposes, as an alternative approach to the study of white identity, the emerging concept of \"dominant ethnicity\", using [[Anthony D. Smith]]'s definition of \"ethnic group\" as a \"named, imagined, human community, many of whose members believe in a myth of shared ancestry and place of origin.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=National Identity|last=Smith|first=Anthony D.|publisher=Penguin|year=1991|isbn=0-14-012565-5|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==List of courses==\n*''U.S. Race Theory & the Problem of Whiteness'', [[Arizona State University]].<ref name=\"washingtonpost2015\"/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[African American studies]]\n*[[Anti-racism]]\n*[[Anti-bias curriculum]]\n*[[Blanqueamiento]]\n*[[Casta]]\n*[[Critical race theory]]\n*[[Historical definitions of race]]\n*[[Identity politics]]\n*[[Postmodernism]]\n*[[Race (classification of human beings)|Race]], for a discussion of the biological concept of race and its applicability to the human population\n*''[[Raising Race Questions]]''\n*[[Social criticism]]\n*[[Social interpretations of race]]\n*[[White people]]\n*[[White privilege]]\n\n==References==\n<!-- ----------------------------------------------------------\n  See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes for a\n  discussion of different citation methods and how to ge